# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: line-of-battle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] The **17th century** lasted from January 1, 1601 (represented by the Roman numerals MDCI), to December 31, 1700 (MDCC).
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] From the mid-17th century, European politics were increasingly dominated by the Kingdom of France of Louis XIV, where royal power was solidified domestically in the civil war of the Fronde.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] The semi-feudal territorial French nobility was weakened and subjugated to the power of an absolute monarchy through the reinvention of the Palace of Versailles from a hunting lodge to a gilded prison, in which a greatly expanded royal court could be more easily kept under surveillance.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] With domestic peace assured, Louis XIV caused the borders of France to be expanded.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] It was during this century that the English monarch became increasingly involved in conflicts with the Parliament, which would culminate in the English civil war and an end to the dominance of the English monarchy.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] It was also a period of development of culture in general (especially theater, music, visual arts and philosophy).
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] Some of the greatest inventions took place in this century.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] It was during this period that the European colonization of the Americas began in earnest, including the exploitation of the silver deposits, which resulted in bouts of inflation as wealth was drawn into Europe.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] Also during this period, there would be a more intense European presence in Southeast Asia and East Asia (such as the colonization of Taiwan).
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] These foreign elements would contribute to a revolution in Ayutthaya.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] The Mataram Sultanate and the Aceh Sultanate would be the major powers of the region, especially during the first half of the century.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] In the Islamic world, the gunpowder empires – the Ottoman, Safavid, and Mughal – grew in strength as well.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] The southern half of India would see the decline of the Deccan Sultanates and extinction of the Vijayanagara Empire.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] The Dutch would colonize Ceylon and endure hostilities with Kandy.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] The end of the 17th century saw the first major surrender of Ottoman territory in Europe when the Treaty of Karlowitz ceded most of Hungary to the Habsburgs in 1699.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] In Japan, Tokugawa Ieyasu established the Tokugawa shogunate at the beginning of the century, beginning the Edo period; the isolationist Sakoku policy began in the 1630s and lasted until the 19th century.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] In China, the collapsing Ming dynasty was challenged by a series of conquests led by the Manchu warlord Nurhaci, which were consolidated by his son Hong Taiji and finally consummated by his grandson, the Shunzhi Emperor, founder of the Qing dynasty.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] Qing China spent decades of this century with economic problems (results of civil wars between the Qing and former Ming dynasty loyalists), only recovering well at the end of the century.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] The greatest military conflicts of the century were the Thirty Years' War, Dutch–Portuguese War, the Great Turkish War, the Nine Years' War, Mughal–Safavid Wars, and the Qing annexation of the Ming.
[src:line-of-battle/17th-century] Major changes in philosophy and science take place, often characterized as the Scientific Revolution.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The **Third Portuguese India Armada** was assembled in 1501 upon the order of King Manuel I of Portugal and placed under the command of João da Nova.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It was small compared to other armadas of the same type and was formed for commercial purposes.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nonetheless, it engaged in the first significant Portuguese naval battle in the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada discovered the uninhabited islands of Ascension and Saint Helena in the South Atlantic Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some speculate that it was the first Portuguese armada to reach Ceylon (now Sri Lanka).
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Little is known about the Third Armada of 1501 as opposed to other early Portuguese India armadas.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Chroniclers' accounts are scant on details and differ significantly at several points.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Very few contemporary documents offer substantive information, such as reconciliations of differing accounts or missing details.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada was primarily a commercial run to India.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It is confirmed to have been composed of four ships: two owned by the crown and two privately owned.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] There may have been a fifth supply ship.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This list of captains is given in João de Barros's *Décadas*, Damião de Góis's *Chronica*, Fernão Lopes de Castanheda's *História*, Diogo do Couto's list, Manuel de Faria e Sousa's *Asia* and Quintella's *Annaes*.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Fernão Pacheco replaces Barbosa in several lists: Gaspar Correia's *Lendas* and the *Relação das Naus*.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The *Livro de Lisuarte de Abreu* replaces Novais and Barbosa with Rui de Abreu and Duarte Pacheco, respectively.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The modest armada carried 350–400 men, only 80 of which were armed.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Its admiral was João da Nova, a Galician-born minor noble.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He was *Alcalde Pequeno* (municipal magistrate) of Lisbon, and his principal recommendation to the admiralship was probably his connection to the powerful Portuguese nobleman Tristão da Cunha.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The owners of the two private ships, D. Álvaro of Braganza and Bartolomeo Marchionni, a Florentine, had jointly outfitted the *Anunciada*, one of the ships of the Second India Armada of Pedro Álvares Cabral that was still at sea at the time.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It was a considerable gamble for them to outfit the new ships before knowing the results of the previous enterprise.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The *Anunciada* safely returned to Lisbon later in 1501 with a large cargo of spices.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It has also been suggested that da Nova was charged to block any attempt by the Spanish to enter the spice trade.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] If true, given the small size of his fleet, he was entrusted with a very delicate mission.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] One of the passengers on the fleet was Paio Rodrigues, employed by D. Álvaro of Braganza to remain in India as a factor for the private consortium.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Another was Álvaro de Braga, a crown factor who was heading for the African port of Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The objective of the Third Armada was wholly commercial.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Its mission was to go to India, load up with spices, and return home.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The journey was expected to be uneventful.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The journey's destination was Calicut (known as *Calecute* in some sources, now Kozhikode), the principal spice hub in the state of Kerala and the dominant city-state on the Malabar coast of India.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada expected – or hoped – that the well-equipped Second India Armada of Pedro Álvares Cabral, which had departed in the previous year (1500), had succeeded in its ambassadorial mission to secure a treaty with Calicut and set up a factory (*feitoria*, a trading hub) there.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada was unaware that Cabral's Second Armada had not only failed in its mission, but it also began hostilities between Portugal and Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] João da Nova's Third Armada was sailing into a war that it did not expect and for which it was not equipped.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada also seems to have had a planned intermediary destination at Sofala, where Cabral had been instructed to set up a factory.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Correia, the crown ship of Francisco de Novais was designated to trade for gold in Sofala and leave the factor Álvaro de Braga, the clerk Diogo Barbosa (same name as captain) and an additional twenty-two men.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Cabral's Second Armada had also already failed that mission: there was no Portuguese factory in Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada could not have delayed its departure until the arrival of the news of the Second Armada.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The seasonal monsoon wind patterns of the Indian Ocean forced India-bound expeditions to leave Lisbon by April at the latest in order to find favorable southeasterly summer winds from Africa to India.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Those same wind patterns determined that returning fleets could only arrive in Europe in the summer, June at the earliest.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although the difference between one fleet's departure and another fleet's arrival was only a few months, outbound fleets could not delay their departure until the previous year's fleet returned; if they did, an entire year would be lost.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Therefore, both the crown and the private consortiums were willing to equip and launch the Third Armada in March 1501 before they received any news of the outcome of the Second Armada.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The first ship of the Second Armada to arrive only did so in late June.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova's Third Armada would learn of the Second Armada's voyage along its own voyage from notes and letters left by Cabral's ships at African staging posts.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Even if the Third Armada learned about the misfortune of the Second Armada, the aforementioned conditions meant that it could not go home to acquire reinforcements or otherwise change the circumstances of its journey.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Lightly armed, it would have to press on, sneak into India stealthily, avoid Calicut, load spices at friendly ports, and leave, all as quickly as possible.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The date of the third Portuguese armada's departure from Lisbon to India has variously been quoted as 1 March, 5 March, 11 March, 26–27 March or 10 April.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Two chronicles claimed the ships discovered Ascension Island during the outward voyage, naming it Conception Island.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Thus, João de Barros wrote that passing eight degrees beyond the equator, towards the south, an island was found to which the name Concepcão was given whilst Damião de Góis’ later chronicle described the sighting of an island south of the line which was named Conçeicam.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] There are at least three reasons why it is thought this name was quoted by de Barros in error, this later being repeated by de Góis.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] First, the Church of Rome has long celebrated the feast of the Immaculate Conception of the Virgin Mary on the fixed date of 8 December, yet by then the third armada had already reached India.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Second, the Portuguese Cantino Planisphere, completed in 1502 after the third armada returned, shows the newly sighted island marked as *ilha achada e chamada Ascenssam* [island found and called Ascension], not as Conception.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Third, in 1503 a division of the 4th Portuguese India Armada (Gama, 1502) under Estêvão da Gama also named the island as Ascension, not as Conception.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It is usually presumed that the island was discovered on the movable feast of Ascension Day, which fell on 20 May in 1501, 39 days after Easter.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Two sources, a letter from King Manuel I of Portugal and Gaspar Corrêa’s chronicle, made no mention of either Ascension or Conception, instead describing a visit to Brazil.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The fleet crossed the Cape of Good Hope on July 7, 1501 without a known incident.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It anchored at Mossel Bay (*Aguada de São Brás*).
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] There, Nova found a note in a shoe by a watering hole.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The note was left about a month earlier by Pêro de Ataíde, one of the captains of the returning Second Armada.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Ataíde's note, addressed to all captains bound for India, warned that Calicut had become hostile to the Portuguese, but that Cochin (*Cochim*, now Kochi) and Cannanore (now Kannur) were still friendly ports where spices could be procured.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It also recommended India-bound captains to go to Malindi, where Pedro Álvares Cabral left letters that contained more detailed information.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Centuries later, the South African government declared the milkwood tree where Ataíde hung his shoe a national monument and erected a shoe-shaped postbox below it.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] A letter written by Pedro Quaresma to King Manuel II described a visit to this location a few years later in 1506.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This same reference source includes a description of the walls of a ruined *hermida* dedicated to St Blaise on the high ground (Cape St Blaise) between two coves at Mossel Bay in 1576.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Later in his outward voyage, Da Nova is also said to have discovered what has since been called Juan de Nova Island in the Mozambique Channel.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In the middle of July 1501, the Third Armada arrived at Mozambique Island.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Disregarding instructions, Nova decided against dispatching Novais's ship to Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova probably concluded that he needed to take all of his men due to the threat of a military engagement in India.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Soon after, he set sail up the East African coast.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] At the same time, Nova possibly discovered Juan de Nova Island in the Mozambique Channel and the Farquhar atoll, part of the Seychelles, which were named the "João da Nova islands" until the 19th century.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Around the same time, the armada arrived at the Swahili citadel of Kilwa (*Quiloa*).
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] A Portuguese *degredado* (convict exile), António Fernandes, greeted them on the beach or on a rowboat.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Barros and Góis, he was António Fernandes, who carried letters from Cabral; Correia writes that he was Pêro Esteves, who was carrying no letters.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The *degredado* informed Nova of the state of affairs in Kilwa.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Barros suggests that, on this occasion, João da Nova personally met Muhammad Arcone, a Kilwan noble who would later play a critical role in Portuguese–Kilwan affairs.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia notes that Nova was wary of approaching Kilwa, and refused to go ashore despite repeated invitations; he had the degredado negotiate the provision of some supplies, probably citrus fruit, from the city for his scurvy-sick crews and hurriedly moved on.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Barros suggests that in late July, the Third Armada immediately set sail for India after it left Kilwa.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia claims that Nova sailed first to Malindi to deliver a letter from King Manuel I of Portugal to the Sultan of Malindi.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Correia, the sultan received the Portuguese well, supplying them amply with biscuits, rice, butter, chickens, sheep and other foods.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He further writes that it was now that Nova received the letters that Cabral had dispatched by a messenger from Mozambique, from which he learned more about the Zamorin (monarch) of Calicut, the Portuguese factory at Cochin and the friendly relations with Cannanore and Quilon.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In this version, the Third Armada left Malindi on July 28, 1501, and crossed the Indian Ocean after 18 days.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In August 1501, João da Nova's Third Armada arrived in India at the Santa Maria islands off the Malabar coast.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to Correia, Nova named the islands because of the feast of the Assumption of Mary (August 15).
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Narratives about the ensuing events differ.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Both narratives agree that the Third Armada eventually began going down the Indian coast to Kerala, attempting to capture two merchant ships, allegedly from Calicut, near Mount d'Eli (now Ezhimala Hill) along the way.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The two-month delay between the Third Armada's reputed arrival in India (August) and its first recorded activities in India (November) has been subject to speculation.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia suggests that the Third Armada simply lingered in the area between Batecala and Mount d'Eli to trade and perhaps engage in piracy before it headed south to Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Others hypothesize that during this interlude, Nova launched exploratory ventures far to the south below Cape Comorin to locate the fabled island of Taprobana (Ceylon), the world's main source of cinnamon.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada arrived in Cannanore in November.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] They were well received by the Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore, who immediately urged João da Nova to load his ships with spices from the city's markets.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova rejected the offer because he first had to collect the supplies already acquired by the Portuguese factory in Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Before leaving, Nova left a few agents with instructions to purchase spices, principally ginger and cinnamon, in Cannanore to be loaded later.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some sources note that Nova established the Portuguese factory in Cannanore at this point.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, the factor whom he left behind was Paio Rodrigues, a private agent of D. Álvaro of Braganza and the Marchionni consortium, not an employee of the Casa da India, the crown trading house.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Casa itself, a proxy of the Portuguese Crown, would only install a factor in Cannanore with the Fourth Armada.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] While he was in Cannanore, João da Nova received an embassy from the Zamorin of Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Accompanying the embassy was Gonçalo Peixoto, a Portuguese survivor of the previous year's massacre who had remained in Calicut for the past year.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In a letter to Nova, the Zamorin expressed sadness at the Calicut Massacre of December 1500, blaming it on hatred between Muslims and Christians that he never understood.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He claimed that he, as a Hindu prince, only had a desire for friendship and peace with Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Zamorin also reported that the ringleaders of the riot had been rounded up and punished, and invited Nova to Calicut to collect the wares left behind in the Portuguese factory and receive compensation.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Proposing to dispatch two ambassadors with Nova's fleet back to Lisbon, he expressed a desire to make a final treaty with King Manuel I of Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore recommended Nova to accept the offer.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Gonçalo Peixoto warned Nova to reject the offer, claiming that the Zamorin was luring him into a trap and at the time preparing a war fleet in Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova did not reply to the Zamorin's entreaty.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Correia asserts that Peixoto did not come; Nova agreed to the offer from the Zamorin's emissary to Cannanore and sailed to Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada anchored by the harbor there, waiting for the promised wares to be shipped from shore, when an unnamed Christian came aboard and warns him about the Zamorin's intentions.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Before Nova left, he captured three merchant ships, including one owned by the Zamorin himself, at the mouth of Calicut harbor.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He seized their cargoes and burned the vessels in plain view of the city.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Valuable loot from the ships included silver Indian nautical instruments, and navigational charts.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Arriving in Cochin, João da Nova encountered a factor left by Cabral, Gonçalo Gil Barbosa, who reports trading difficulties in the local markets.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Indian spice merchants required payment in silver, but Cabral had left the factor only with Portuguese goods, mainly cloth.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He was expected to use the trading revenue from the sale of the Portuguese goods to buy spices.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, the Portuguese wares had little value in Indian markets, so Barbosa still had his unsold stock and was unable to obtain silver to buy spices.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The factor suspected that Arab merchant guilds had engineered a boycott of Portuguese goods in India.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He also reported that the Trimumpara Raja of Cochin, despite his alliance and protection of the factory, was furious at the Portuguese because Cabral's Second Armada had departed too suddenly, not taking two noble Cochinese noble hostages with it.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Sources ascribe the lack of silver cash as the pressing problem that Nova did not anticipate.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] He did not bring much because he expected to raise cash through selling Portuguese goods.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova immediately set sail back to Cannanore to see if the agents whom he left there had raised cash, but they faced the same problem.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore finally intervened, placing himself as security for the sale of spices to the Portuguese on credit and allowing the Portuguese to obtain spices.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In 1898, excavations underneath the Breakwater Office in Colombo, Sri Lanka, revealed a boulder with a Portuguese inscription, a coat of arms, and the clearly denoted date 1501.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] That was four years before Lourenço de Almeida's arrival on the island, the formal date (1505) of the Portuguese discovery of Ceylon.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Much speculation has surrounded the inscription.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The earliest theory was that the boulder was an uncompleted gravestone for a Portuguese captain born in 1501 (death date missing).
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, the arms and style of the inscription appeared to be of a *padrão*, the typical marker of a Portuguese claim.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some argue that the date is simply a mistake or that the "1" in 1501 is a poorly carved digit.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Another theory is that what appears to be a number is actually an acronym, ISOI (*Iesus Salvator Orientalium Indicorum* – "Jesus the Savior of the East Indies").
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nonetheless, some historians, notably Bouchon in 1980, have argued that the inscription was made by a captain of the Third Armada of 1501.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The sources that describe the journey of the armada do not record that it stumbled upon Ceylon, but the journey of the armada was poorly recorded as a whole.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Bouchon (1980) speculates that the discovery happened during an exploratory venture launched from Anjediva Island or the Santa Maria islands.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] 257) is that the journey to Ceylon was sometime in late November or early December 1501.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Under this scenario, Nova did not immediately return to Cannanore after he realized the cash problem, but rather he or one of his captains either stumbled upon Ceylon or was guided there by a local, hoping for better success there.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] None of these theories are confirmed or suggested in any written accounts.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In mid-December 1501, the Third Armada was preparing to leave India, loaded with spices from Cannanore and other goods from piratical attacks.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] News arrived, however, that a battle fleet led by the Zamorin was approaching.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Sometime in December, Nova's fleet was cornered by the Zamorin's fleet as he was about to leave Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Zamorin's fleet comprised nearly 40 large ships, and 180 small ships called *paraus* and *zambuks*.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Raja of Cannanore urged Nova to stay under his protection and avoid conflict.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova rejected the Raja's offer, attempting to break out with a favorable breeze.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Third Armada fired its cannons to breach the Zamorin's line.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Once a breach was opened, four Portuguese ships charged into the breach in a column formation, their side cannons blasting.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The pounding from the cannons and the height of Nova's ships prevented the Calicut forces from boarding the Portuguese ships with grappling hooks.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The less seaworthy fleet of the Zamorin, pursuing the escaping Portuguese, began to splinter due to intense cannon fire.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The increased distance between the slowed-down Calicut fleet and the Third Armada caused the former to stop aiming to board the Portuguese ships, causing the battle to become a ranged artillery duel.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The Calicut fleet retreated after it realized that its cannons' range and reloading speed could not match those of the Third Armada.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova gave a brief chase, finally breaking up the engagement on January 2, 1502.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] After two days of fighting, the Third Armada had sunk five large ships and about a dozen oar-driven boats.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It inflicted great damage on the remaining vessels of the Zamorin while it was not damaged much itself.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although João da Nova was not prepared for a fight, the two-day naval battle off Cannanore is regarded by some as the first significant Portuguese naval engagement in the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It was not the first clash between Portuguese and Indian ships – Vasco da Gama's First Armada and Cabral's Second Armada also fought with various Indian fleets.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Earlier encounters were fought against mostly poorly armed merchant ships, pirates and isolated squads; a single well-armed caravel could win a battle against these targets with ease.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In the First Battle of Cannanore, the Zamorin of Calicut had attacked directly, deploying the best fleet he could against a small group of Portuguese merchant carracks, which were significantly less heavily armed than the ships of Gama and Cabral.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to the Portuguese Navy's official website, the battle is also historically notable for being one of the earliest recorded deliberate uses of a naval column, later called line of battle, and for being resolved by cannon fire alone.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The tactics used in the battle became increasingly prevalent as naval technology and strategy evolved, causing the battle to have been called the first modern naval battle.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In early 1502, the Third Armada captured another Calicut merchant ship near Mount d'Eli, which it sacked, burned and sunk.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It began the return voyage soon afterwards.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada made two watering stops in East Africa: first at Malindi, where Nova deposited letters that would be received later that year by Thomé Lopes, and second at Mozambique Island.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] After turning around the Cape of Good Hope, Nova sailed into the South Atlantic and discovered the uninhabited island of Saint Helena while he was returning home.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] It is believed that the island was named after St.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] By tradition the date is the feast day of the saint on May 21.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Jan Huyghen van Linschoten in a 2015 paper says that the date is a mistakenly quoted Protestant feast day for a discovery made two decades before the Reformation, instead suggesting May 3 as the more likely date, the feast day of the True Cross.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to legend, Nova anchored on the western side of the island and built a timber chapel at the location of the future Jamestown, Saint Helena.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The island became a routine staging post on future Portuguese expeditions to India, but its existence and location was a Portuguese secret for the next eighty years until English captain Thomas Cavendish stumbled upon it in 1588.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova's Third Armada arrived in Lisbon on September 11, 1502.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] According to the letters by Italian merchants in Lisbon, the Third Armada brought back 900 *cantari* (quintals) of black pepper, 550 of cinnamon, 30 of ginger, 25 of lac, and other assorted goods.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The amount of cinnamon has been cited as evidence of the theory that the armada visited Ceylon, but cinnamon was not rare in other Indian markets.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Some of the cinnamon may have come from the cargoes of seized vessels.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The expedition of the Third Armada was not considered a resounding success.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although there was no significant loss of ships or men, the armada came back with fewer spices than had been anticipated; letters insinuate that the cargo holds were partially empty.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Nova also failed to trade for gold in Africa.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The report of the cash constraint in India and the armada's reliance on piracy to fill its holds disheartened Portuguese merchants, who had previously thought that they could make easy profits on both legs of the India run.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] In contrast, the discovery of Ascension Island and Saint Helena was well received.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The armada arrived too late to supply information from the journey to Gama's heavily armed 4th India Armada, which had already left Lisbon.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] By long tradition Saint Helena was sighted on 21 May 1502 by the four ships of the 3rd Portuguese Armada commanded by João da Nova during the return voyage to Lisbon, and that he named it Santa Helena after Saint Helena of Constantinople.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This tradition has been reviewed by a 2022 paper which concluded the Portuguese chronicles published at least 50 years later, are the sole primary source to the discovery.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Although contradictory in describing other events, these chronicles almost unanimously claim João da Nova found Saint Helena sometime in 1502, although none quote the precise date.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] However, there are several reasons for doubting da Nova made this discovery.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Second, when a section of the Fourth Armada under the command of Estêvão da Gama sighted and landed at Saint Helena the following year on 30 July 1503 its scrivener Thomé Lopes regarded it as an unknown island yet named Ascension as one of five reference points to the new island’s location.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] On 12 July 1502, nearly three weeks before reaching Saint Helena, Lopes described how Estêvão da Gama’s ships met up with a section of the Fifth Armada led by Afonso de Albuquerque off the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The latter left Lisbon about six months after João da Nova’s return so Albuquerque and his captains should all have known whether João da Nova had indeed found Saint Helena.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] An anonymous Flemish traveler on one of da Gama's ships reporting that bread and victuals were running short by the time they reached the Cape, so from da Gama's perspective there was a pressing need that he be told water and meat could be found at Saint Helena.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The fact that nothing seems to have been said about the island, da Gama's scrivener Lopes regarding the island as unknown, again implies da Nova found Ascension but not Saint Helena.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The 2022 paper also reviews cartographic evidence that Saint Helena and Ascension were known to the Spanish in 1500, before either João da Nova or Estêvão da Gama sailed for India.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The suggestion that João da Nova discovered Tristan da Cunha naming it Saint Helena is discounted.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] If João da Nova indeed found Saint Helena, a separate 2015 paper has reviewed another tradition that he did so on 21 May 1502.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This date appears to have first been suggested by Jan Huyghen van Linschoten in a book published in Holland in 1596.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This described how his ships left Saint Helena on 21 May 1589, this being both the feast of Saint Helena and Whitsunday.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] At first sight, this statement seems to be a contradiction - the Roman Catholic Church certainly celebrated Whitsunday that day but their feast-day of Saint Helena was on 18 August.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Linschoten's statement did not fit in with the Eastern Orthodox Church either - this faith certainly marked Saint Helena on 21 May but in 1589 celebrated Whitsun a week later, on 28 May.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The paper suggested the solution to this apparent paradox was that by the time his book was published in 1596 Linschoten had converted to the Protestant Dutch Reformed Church.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] This faith celebrated Whitsunday on the same day as Catholics while Saint Helena was marked on 21 May, the same day as the Orthodox Church.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] Quite apart from the fact that the discoverers were Catholics, Linschoten failed to realise the impossibility that the island was named after a Protestant feast-day, it being found more than a decade before the Reformation and start of Protestantism.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] An alternative discovery date of 3 May on the Catholic feast-day celebrating the finding of the True Cross by Saint Helena in Jerusalem, as quoted by Odoardo Duarte Lopes in 1591 and by Sir Thomas Herbert in 1638, is suggested as historically more credible than the Protestant date of 21 May.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] News of Cabral's discovery reached Lisbon directly from South America before da Nova's fleet set off on the voyage to India in 1501.
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] If da Nova knew the True Cross name had already been assigned, the most obvious and plausible alternative name for him to give the island was "Santa Helena".
[src:line-of-battle/3rd-portuguese-india-armada-nova-1501] The long tradition that João da Nova built a chapel from one of his wrecked carracks has been shown to be based on a misreading of the records.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The **4th Portuguese India Armada** was a Portuguese fleet that sailed from Lisbon in February, 1502.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Along the way, in East Africa, the 4th Armada established a Portuguese factory in present-day Mozambique, made contact and opened trade with the gold entrepot of Sofala and extorted tribute from Kilwa.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Once in India, the armada set about attacking Calicut shipping and disrupting trade along much of the Malabar Coast.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But the ruling Zamorin of Calicut refused to accede to Portuguese demands, arguing that the violent exactions of the armada exceeded any claims they might have for compensation.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The 4th Armada left without bringing the Zamorin to terms and leaving matters unresolved.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Before departing, the armada established a crown factory in Cannanore and left behind a small patrol under Vicente Sodré, the first permanent Portuguese fleet in the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Second India Armada, commanded by Pedro Álvares Cabral, had arrived in Portugal in the summer of 1501 in a terrible shape.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Ship and human losses were tremendous, its mission objectives failed.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] By the time this news was received, the 3rd India Armada under João da Nova had already departed, a commercial expedition unequipped to deal with the hostile turn of events in the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As a result, King Manuel I of Portugal ordered a new fleet to be assembled, the 4th India Armada, armed to the teeth, with the explicit objective of bringing Calicut to heel.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The command of the 4th Armada was offered to Pedro Álvares Cabral.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But various factions in the Portuguese court and the Casa da India, opposed Cabral's appointment, on the grounds that it was Cabral's 'incompetence' that had created this unhappy situation to begin with.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] However, Cabral had his own political supporters that could not be ignored.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Finding this condition an unacceptable affront, Cabral withdrew his name in a huff.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Manuel I immediately appointed Vasco da Gama himself as captain-major.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The intrigues behind the appointment have been variously told.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] By some accounts, the initial offer to Cabral was a *pro forma* gesture to palliate his faction rather than an earnest offer.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] In other words, the king never had any intention of letting Cabral lead the expedition, that the onerous conditions were introduced knowing Cabral would find them unacceptable.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] That these conditions were only revealed at the last minute, just before the fleet's departure, lends credence to the theory, i.e. the monarch did not want to give Cabral time to reconsider or allow opposition to mount against Gama's rapid appointment.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On this hint, Gama produced a royal letter (issued by Manuel back in 1500, and reiterated in October 1501), promising Gama a determining role in any future India expedition, and demanded command of the expedition for himself.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The king was caught between two commitments – honoring the letter to Gama, or his appointment to Cabral.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Hearing of the king's quandary, Cabral voluntarily withdrew his name to graciously allow Manuel I to honor his letter.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The 16th-century chroniclers seem to agree that King Manuel I wanted to deprive Cabral of command, and that the Sodré appointment and/or the Gama letter was just a ploy by the king to wiggle out of appointing Cabral.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But some later authors have interpreted the accounts differently, that King Manuel I was wholly behind Cabral, but was forced to yield to the unsavory machinations of the Gama-Sodré family.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The *vintena* would continue until 1522.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The 4th Armada was composed of 20 ships and between 800 and 1800 men.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Armada was originally envisaged as two squadrons – 15 ships under the admiral to head to India, 5 under the vice-admiral designated to patrol the mouth of the Red Sea.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The exact composition of the three squadrons differs in the various accounts.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The following list of ships should not be regarded as authoritative, but a tentative list compiled from various conflicting accounts.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] This list of captains is principally based on João de Barros's *Décadas*, Damião de Gois's *Chronica*, Castanheda's *História*, the *Relação das Náos*, Couto's list, Faria e Sousa's *Asia* and Quintella's *Annaes da Marinha*.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The list of ship names is from Gaspar Correia's *Lendas da Índia*. and should be suspected as unreliable.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As usual, Correia's list of captains differs significantly from the others.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The anonymous lists of the *Memorias das Armadas* and *Livro de Lisuarte de Abreu* give their own variations.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Doubtless, the captain lists are complicated by the fact that there were some rearrangements of the fleet in Africa and India, and captains were shuffled around – at some point, both Vicente and Brás Sodré was definitely given command of a ship of his own.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The chronicles report that the fleet also carried pre-fabricated lumber and fittings with instructions to assemble a new caravel upon arrival in East Africa.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The most famous ship in the 4th Armada was arguably the one commanded by Estevão da Gama, the *Flor de la Mar* (sometimes spelled as *Frol de la Mar*), a 400 tonne carrack (*nau*), the largest ship of that kind yet built.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The exact sizes of the other large carracks – the flagship *São Jerónimo*, *Lionarda* and the *Leitoa*/*Esmeralda* are unknown, but also presumed to be quite sizeable (that is, 250t or greater).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] These large ships were designated to return with spice cargo back to Lisbon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The smaller naus(*navetas*, 80–120t) and caravels (40–80t), went out as armed fighting ships, to remain as naval patrol vessels in India if necessary.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Gama clan dominated the fleet – Vasco da Gama, his cousin Estêvão da Gama and his uncles Vicente Sodré and Brás Sodré took the leadership positions.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] We have assumed Pêro de Ataíde, to be the same person nicknamed 'o Inferno' ('Hell'), a notable veteran captain of Cabral's Second Armada.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But in some accounts, his name is given as 'Álvaro de Ataíde' a native of the Algarve, thus possibly Vasco da Gama's new brother-in-law (Gama had recently married Catarina de Ataíde in 1500 or 1501; she had a brother by that name).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Lopo Mendes de Vasconcellos was a soon-to-be brother-in-law (betrothed to Teresa da Gama, Vasco's sister).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Among the remaining captains, the most significant was probably *Dom* Luís Coutinho, son of the Count of Marialva, a high nobleman of considerable rank in the Portuguese court.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Diogo Fernandes Correia (archaically, Corrêa) was pre-designated by the Casa da India as the factor for Cochin (replacing the factor Gonçalo Gil Barbosa that Cabral had left there).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] There was significant private participation in the fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Two ships went out under Italian captains – Tomásio da Cremona ('Thomas de Carmona') and Giovanni Buonagrazia ('João da Bonagracia') of Florence.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The *Leitoa Nova* is said to have been privately outfitted by the powerful nobleman Tristão da Cunha in conjunction with the mysterious Lisbon merchant-woman Catarina Dias de Aguiar Eyewitness accounts suggest three more ships were also privately outfitted.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] There were two Italian passengers on the armada – both military engineers, and probably secret Venetian agents – that would play a sinister role in India.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They were known by their Portuguese names as João Maria (Gianmaria) and Pêro António (Pierantonio).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Carmona's ship (6) letters dispatched from Lisbon by Italian agents Francesco Corbinelli and Giovanni Francesco Affaitati drawn from interviews with the newly returning crews in August 1503.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The principal mission of the 4th Armada was to settle scores with the Zamorin of Calicut; The armada was to avenge the Zamorin's mistreatment of Cabral and the massacre of the Portuguese in the Calicut factory.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As they did not have enough manpower to conquer Calicut outright, the armada planned to use their first squadron to set up a naval blockade in Calicut harbor, while the second squadron under Vicente Sodré would patrol the Gulf of Aden and cut off all further Arab shipping in the Red Sea.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] This would severely disrupt Calicut's trade and therefore its economic lifeline – a show of force to intimidate the Zamorin into compliance.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Armada would then demand that the Zamorin replace the damaged factory of the 2nd Armada, that he expel all Arabs from the Calicut region as punishment for their involvement in the aforementioned massacre, and that he sign a trade treaty regarding the supply of spice to Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Additionally, 4th Armada was instructed to open trade with the East African city-state of Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Sofala had been secretly visited by the explorer Pêro da Covilhã during his overland expedition back in 1487, and he identified it as the end-point of the Monomatapa gold trade.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Portuguese crown had been eager to tap that gold source, but all prior armadas had failed to find it until Sancho de Tovar, commanding a ship of the 2nd India Armada, had finally located Sofala the previous year, but he only saw it from afar and did not go ashore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] It seems that every ship in this armada was issued explicit royal instructions to try to trade for gold in Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] February 10, 1502, Two squadrons of the 4th Armada – 10 ships under admiral Vasco da Gama and 5 ships under vice-admiral Vicente Sodré– set out from Lisbon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Late February, 1502 – Fleet anchors in Senegal (either at *Porto de Ale* (Sali Portudal) or *Bezeguiche* (Bay of Dakar)) to take water.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] It is reported in one chronicle that Fernan d'Atouguia, captain of the *Leitoa Nova* falls ill and dies here.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama transfers the experienced captain Pedro Afonso de Aguiar from the small nau *Santa Elena* to the large nau *Leitoa Nova*, and elevates one of his own companions, Pêro de Mendonça, to captain Aguiar's old ship.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Early March, 1502 – The 4th Armada sails southwest from Africa and may make a brief watering stop at Cape St.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Augustine (Brazil), before heading across the south Atlantic towards the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] April 1, 1502, The third squadron of the 4th Armada – five ships under Estêvão da Gama – finally sets out from Lisbon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Charting its own course, the third squadron will only catch up with the main body of the 4th Armada in India.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] April–May, 1502 Violent storms at the Cape separates the fifteen ships of Vasco da Gama's fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Each captain is forced to figure out his own passage around the Cape, and make his own way towards the pre-arranged rendez-vous point on the other side.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] May, 1502 After making watering stops in Madeira and Cape Verde, Estevão da Gama's third squadron reportedly spots an island in the south Atlantic.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Uncertain which one – could be a Cape Verde island or the Penedo de São Pedro (islets off the Brazilian coast) or even as far as the islands of Trindade and Martim Vaz (further south), but does not stop to investigate.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] (By coincidence, that very same month, the returning Third Armada of João da Nova discovers the island of Saint Helena; despite the timing, the returning fleet will not encounter any of the ships of the outward armada.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] June 10, 1502 – Chronicles differ on what exactly happens after the first squadrons double the Cape.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Following the account of Gaspar Correia (p.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] 272), Vasco da Gama was among the first ships to arrive in Mozambique Island, the pre-arranged meeting point.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama is immediately recognized by the local sheikh (with whom Gama had a tussle on his first journey back in 1498).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The Mozambique ruler immediately offers his pardon for that affair and puts supplies at the disposal of the tempest-tossed Portuguese.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Vasco da Gama remains in Mozambique for a while, waiting for the rest of the battered fleet to trickle in, one by one.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The only known loss is the small nau *Santa Elena*, captained by the novice Pêro de Mendonça, which captured by bad currents around Cape Correntes, ends up running aground near the banks of Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] However the crew is safely rescued by the passing ships of Francisco da Cunha Mareco (*Bretoa*) and Fernão Rodrigues Bardaças (*Santa Marta*).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] With surfeit of crew from the capsized *Santa Elena*, Gama orders the construction of a whole new caravel from scratch on Mozambique Island.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Although not mentioned in all sources, the caravel of António do Campo ('Antão Vaz' in Correia), is said to have been badly battered at Cape Correntes, and drifted backwards into Delagoa Bay (Maputo).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Campo will not rejoin the 4th Armada on time for the Indian Ocean crossing, and thus remain stuck in Africa until next year.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] According to Correia, while repairing on Mozambique Island, Vasco da Gama dispatches Pedro Afonso de Aguiar (captain of the *Leitoa*) and two caravels south to the city of Sofala, the entrepot of the Monomatapa gold trade.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Sofala had been missed by all prior armadas, but not this time.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Following up on the scout report of Sancho de Tovar from the previous year (see 2nd India Armada), Aguiar leads the first Portuguese ships into Sofala harbor.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Aguiar goes ashore, initiates some trade in the local markets while seeking out the local ruler, the sultan or shiekh Isuf of Sofala (*Yçuf* in Barros; *Çufe* in Goes).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] An audience is arranged and Aguiar draws up a commercial and alliance treaty between Portugal and Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Matters settled and gifts exchanged, Aguiar takes aboard a Sofalese ambassador to meet Vasco da Gama back in Mozambique.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] In other accounts, (principally Osório (p.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] 192), mildly corroborated by other chroniclers and the anonymous Portuguese eyewitness and Matteo da Bergamo) it is Vasco da Gama himself, and not Aguiar, who goes to Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] After accounting for all the ships and sending them on to Mozambique, Vasco da Gama himself sailed south with four ships to Sofala, conducted some trade and opened the first contact with the Sofalese ruler.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] That would mean Gama was the last to arrive in Mozambique.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] In this alternative account, the lost ship of Mendonça (or Fernandes) was one of the four that went with Gama to Sofala, and capsized while exiting the Sofala banks.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Late June, 1502 – Vasco da Gama makes arrangements to leave Mozambique.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] A Portuguese factory is established on Mozambique Island, with Gonçalo Baixo as the factor, with some ten assistants, to capitalize on the results of the Sofala trade mission.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The new caravel finished, Gama christens it *Pomposa* and places it, together with some 30 crew, under the command of João Serrão (of future Magellan fame), with instructions to take any goods from the Sofalese trade.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] According to Correia, Gama was unwilling to wait around for the results of Aguiar's mission to Sofala, and set sail out of Mozambique before Aguiar's returned from Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As a result, Aguiar was forced to leave the Sofalese ambassador in Mozambique (letting him find his own way back home) and set sail for Malindi, hoping to catch Gama there.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama had gone first to Kilwa (*Quiloa*).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The dominant city-state on the East African coast, Kilwa Sultanate was the formal overlord of Mozambique and Sofala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] If the fledgling Portuguese trade presence in those East African towns was to remain unmolested, then the Portuguese must secure Kilwa's consent.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Cabral and the 2nd Armada had tried, and failed, to secure a treaty with Kilwa back in 1500.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama decided to try again – and was determined not to take no for answer.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] But, mindful of the lesson at Calicut, Gama also wanted to add a touch of intimidation, to show off his heavily armed fleet and impress upon the Sultan of Kilwa the consequences of interfering or turning back on any agreement.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On July 12, 1502, Gama's large, menacing armada arrived at the island-city of Kilwa.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama sent for the Kilwa ruler, Emir Ibrahim, inviting him aboard the *São Jeronimo*, to negotiate a treaty of peace and trade.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Sensing a trap, Emir Ibrahim first asks for a safe-conduct (which da Gama promptly gives him), but fearing treachery, the emir changes his mind, and refuses to go aboard.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] However, after much discussion, one of his advisors, a certain wealthy nobleman Muhammad ibn Rukn ad Din (called Muhammad Arcone or Ancone or Enconij by the chroniclers ) finally persuades the emir to take up the Portuguese offer.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Emir Ibrahim is ferried to the flagship and climbs aboard.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] After minimal opening cordialities, and ostentatious proclamations of friendship, Gama lays down his price: a treaty with Portugal has to be paid for with a hefty cash tribute to the King of Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Declaring tribute to be a dishonor, he refuses.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama threatens to level the city and lay it to fire and waste.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Emir Ibrahim, effectively captive on board, reluctantly agrees, and signs a treaty making Kilwa tributary to Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Leaving the Kilwan nobleman and advisor Muhammad Arcone aboard as a hostage, the emir returns to shore to make the arrangements.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] mid-July, 1502 – After a few days of lingering in Kilwa harbor and no sign of the emir's promised tribute, Gama dispatches a messenger to see what the delay is.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Emir Ibrahim sends a message back declining to dispatch the tribute, and telling the Portuguese captain-major that he can do whatever he will with the hostage Muhammad Arcone, given that his poor counsel had proven him unworthy.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The angry Gama throws Arcone into a long-boat, without water or shade, to die of heat and exposure.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Nonetheless, Muhammad Arcone is a wealthy man in his own right, and servants from his household offer Gama a substantial ransom to release him.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Knowing the hostage is otherwise worthless to him, Gama consents.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] July 20, 1502 – His vengeance on Muhammad Arcone's bad counsel satisfied, the Emir Ibrahim of Kilwa finally decides to send some tribute – some 1500 gold *meticals* – to satisfy the Portuguese captain-major.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Vasco da Gama, anxious not to miss the monsoon winds to India, takes what he can get.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] [The extorted gold coins of Kilwa were used by the goldsmith Gil Vicente in 1506 to make the famous gold pyx or monstrance known as the *Custódia de Belém*, for the Jerónimos Monastery in Belém.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] 282) reports a little knot before departing: several dozen Kilwan women 'picked up' (read: abducted) and taken aboard the ships by bored Portuguese sailors for fun and amusement refuse to return ashore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Although Emir Ibrahim promises that they will be unharmed, he cannot guarantee that those who allowed themselves to be baptized Christian by enthusiastic chaplains on the ships will be taken back by their families.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] July 15, 1502, In the meantime, part of the third squadron, the trio that held with Estêvão da Gama (Gama, Dias, Carmona) arrive at Mozambique Island, half-famished and heavily damaged.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] At that same time, the remaining pair (Vasconcellos, Buonagrazia) alight at the Sofala banks.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The two squads do not reconnect with each other.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Estêvão da Gama's trio, following the itinerary left in Mozambique by his cousin, heads off to Kilwa Alone idling before Sofala, Vasconcellos and Buonagrazia proceed north to the mouth of the *Rio de Bons Sinaes* (Zambezi River), where they put in for repairs and recuperation.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On July 23, 1502, part of the third squad (Estêvão da Gama, Lopo Dias and Thomas de Carmona) arrived in Kilwa, just in time to reconnect the main armada of Vasco da Gama, preparing to depart from Kilwa harbor.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] At that moment (July 22 actually), the remaining two ships of the third squad (Vasconcellos, Buonagrazia) finally arrive in Mozambique Island.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Taking note of the notes and itinerary left behind, they set sail for Malindi, hoping to catch the main fleet there.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Late July, 1502 – Vasco da Gama arrives in Malindi, just in time to be met by Pedro Afonso de Aguiar (from Sofala), who reports to him the results of the Sofala treaty.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Gama's fleet does not actually dock in Malindi – they intended to, but miss it, landing a few leagues ahead, unable to turn back because of the weather (although they manage to get some supplies and exchange messages with Malindi emissaries that row out to them).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] On July 29, 1502, Vasco da Gama's fleet departed its anchorage near Malindi for its Indian Ocean crossing.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] He was missing three ships: *Campo*, *Vasconcelos* and *Buonagrazia*.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] August 2, 1502 – The remaining two ships of the third squadron (Lopo Mendes de Vasconcelos and Giovanni Buonagrazia) arrive in Malindi, just a few days after Gama's departure.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They are well received by the Sultan of Malindi.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They pick up a few letters left with degredado Luiz da Moura in Malindi by the returning fleet of João da Nova a few months earlier, reporting the latest Indian news.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] They do not stay long, but immediately set sail after Gama's fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The last missing ship – António do Campo's caravel from the first squadron – will not make it across to India this year.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] As already alluded to earlier, the caravel of António do Campo ('Antão Vaz' in Correia) is said to have been caught up and battered by bad winds at Cape Correntes and forced to drift with the current of the Mozambique Channel aimlessly southwest.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Campo's caravel is said to have alighted at Delagoa Bay (now Maputo Bay).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The hitherto unknown capacious bay is watered by three rivers: the Maputo river to the south, the Espirito Santo 'river' to the west (actually an estuary formed by the Umbeluzi, Matola and Tembe rivers) and the Maniça (now Incomati) river to the north.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Being told by the local inhabitants that the Espírito Santo 'river' was sourced from a great lake deep in the interior, Campo names it *Rio da Lagoa* (River of the Lagoon), from which we get the name by which Maputo Bay was long known: 'Delagoa Bay'.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] Having been forced to linger at Delagoa for repairs, António do Campo hurries north to try to make junction with the rest of the 4th Armada at Malindi, but arrives too late (mid-September).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] The fleet having already left for India, and the monsoon winds preventing Campo's own crossing to India.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p01] António do Campo will remain behind on the East African coast until next April.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] mid-August, 1502 – After its Indian Ocean crossing, the 4th Armada alights near the opulent port of Dabul (north of Goa).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] These are the territorial waters of the powerful Muslim sultan Adil Shah (*Hidalcão*) of Bijapur.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Expecting trouble, the fighting ships hoist up their lateen sails and load up their cannon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But no one comes out to challenge them, so they begin coasting south along the Indian coast towards Kerala.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] August 20, 1502 Gama's fleet reaches Anjediva island.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The next day, the ships of Giovanni Buonagrazia (carrying Thomé Lopes) and Lopo Mendes de Vasconcellos (*Juiloa*) finally catch up with the rest of the armada.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Save for the ship of Campo (still stuck in Africa) and Serrão (on patrol around the Mozambique factory), all the Portuguese fleet (18 ships out of the 20 that left Lisbon) are together and accounted for.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Around Anjediva island, the armada spots three boats belonging to Timoja, the Hindu privateer who operates out of Honnavar (*Onor*), on the frontline between the warring states of Muslim Bijapur and Hindu Vijayanagar.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They give chase unto the mouth of the Sharavathi River, at which point the pirate boats slip into harbor of Onor.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Assured by Gaspar da Gama (Goese Jew and translator) that Onor is a corsair's nest, Vasco da Gama orders an attack on the city.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese landing crews attack the harbor, plundering and setting fire to the ships and docks.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The day after the raid on Onor, the 4th Armada arrives at the mouth of the river that leads up to the city of Bhatkal (*Batecala*), south of Onor.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Perceiving what he considers hostile gestures from shore, the captain-major dispatches his cousin, Estêvão da Gama upriver to the town to investigate.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Surveying the Batecala docks, Estêvão spies several Arab merchant ships and prepares for hostilities.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But his attention is soon drawn to a small group of men in ornate robes, rushing down to the docks, frantically calling to him.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It is an embassy from the raja of Batecala, requesting an immediate audience with the Portuguese captain-major.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Estêvão brings the embassy to his cousin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Evidently hearing of the fate of Onor, the embassy offers to submit to the Portuguese.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vasco da Gama agrees to leave Batecala in peace in return for a yearly tribute of 1,000 bags of plain rice and 500 bags of quality rice (probably Basmati).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Batecala is also to agree to the exclusion of the Arab merchants from the city, that no pepper trade is to be carried at this port, and that no ship be allowed to travel between Batecala and Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The treaty is set down in writing and signed.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Late August/Early September 1502 – Business in Batecala done, Vasco da Gama sets sail towards Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They anchor in around Mount d'Eli, the common touch-point for ships on the Jedda-Calicut route, evidently intending to catch some prizes before proceeding.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] September 29, 1502 – After prowling around Mt. d'Eli for nearly a month with little success (they captured only one minor ship), captain Gil Matoso (on the *São Gabriel*), spots a large merchant ship carrying Muslim pilgrims returning from Mecca (or going to it, chronicles contradict).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The ship, the *Miri*, is identified as belonging to a certain al-Fanqi, one of wealthier men of Calicut and said by some to be the Meccan factor in Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Matoso chases the pilgrim ship down, which surrenders rather quickly, probably imagining that its master had enough money to ransom it off.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vasco da Gama shrugs off all the offers.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As the Portuguese crew plunder the ship and transfer its cargo, it quickly becomes evident that Gama intends to burn the ship with all its passengers – men, women and children – on board.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] When Gama proves deaf to their pleas for mercy, the passengers frantically attack the Portuguese men-at-arms with their bare hands, to no avail.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 3, 1502 – a day, eyewitness Thomé Lopes states, "I will never forget for the rest of my days".
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The pilgrim ship thoroughly plundered, on Gama's orders, the passengers are locked in the hold and the ship burnt and sunk by artillery.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It takes several days to finally go down completely.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese soldiers row around the waters on longboats mercilessly spearing survivors.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The sinking of the *Miri* is an act that will instantly cement Gama's cruel and fearsome reputation, and generate a great deal of hatred for the Portuguese in India.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama defended his act as "vengeance" for the Calicut massacre of 1500, arguing that the ship's owner, as a prominent person in Calicut, was 'doubtlessly' responsible for the sinister counsel to the Zamorin that led up to it.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Of the eyewitnesses, all mention it, but only Thomé Lopes openly condemns the act, claiming Gama acted "with great cruelty and without any mercy whatsoever".
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The chroniclers do not shy away from describing the event and their unease is evident.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Although Barros and Castanheda reiterate Gama's justification of the act as revenge for Cabral, they do not seem to embrace it themselves.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Indeed, Barros, Góis and Osório claim the ship belonged to the Sultan of Egypt, who was in no way responsible for the events in Calicut, thus subtly suggesting Gama may have made a mistake.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gaspar Correia is a little more open in his disapproval.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He notes that several of the Portuguese captains were appalled by Gama's decision and tried to persuade him against it (if only because they would forego a hefty ransom).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Correia gives a heart-rending account of the desperate and valiant resistance of the doomed passengers.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Poet Luís de Camões passes over the incident in silence, evidently feeling it detrimental to the heroic portrait of Vasco da Gama.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Estimates of those killed on the *Miri* hover around 300.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese chroniclers are eager to report that 20 children were spared this fate, and brought back by the 4th Armada to Lisbon, where they will be baptized and raised as friars at the Nossa Senhora de Belém.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Among the eyewitnesses Thomé Lopes and the anonymous Flemish sailor make no mention of this small mercy, although Matteo de Bergamo does point it out.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 18, 1502 – Vasco da Gama's armada finally reaches Cannanore (*Canonor*, Kannur), and delivers the Cannanore ambassador that had gone to Lisbon with Cabral's 2nd Armada.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Kolathiri Raja of Cannanore invites Gama to come ashore for an elaborate reception, but Gama replies that he swore a personal oath not to set his foot on Indian soil again until his vengeance on Calicut was sated.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As a result, the rajah orders a wooden scaffold to be built over the seashore, where they can meet in person without violating the vow.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama presents the raja with royal letters and munificent gifts (a jeweled sword, a brocaded armchair) and discussions immediately begin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] A commercial treaty is negotiated, establishing a Portuguese crown factory in Cannanore, and arranging a fixed-price schedule, which the Raja personally guarantees, for the sale of spices to the Portuguese.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The negotiation for the commercial treaty did not go smoothly, particularly the fixed price clause.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Kolathiri Raja protested that he had no power over market prices nor the right to dictate how private merchants disposed of their property.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama had to resort to feints, threats and then sailed out of Cannanore in anger.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Barros credits the role of Paio Rodrigues, the Portuguese factor (private, not crown, an employee of the private employee of D. Álvaro of Braganza and the Marchionni consortium), that had been left behind in Cannanore by João da Nova's Third Armada at the beginning of the year.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Correia points out this is the treaty where the Portuguese *cartaz* system was first introduced.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Henceforth, every merchant ship along the Malabar coast had to present a certificate signed by a Portuguese factor (in Cannanore, Cochin, etc.), or else be subject to attack and seizure by a Portuguese patrol.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] This licensing system would be subsequently adopted later on other Portuguese-controlled coasts (e.g.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] East Africa, Malacca, Brazil), with differing degrees of success.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It will be largely maintained until the 18th century.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 25, 1502 – Fleet departs Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Chroniclers differ a little on the subsequent sequence of events.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] While still in Cannanore, Gama had sent Pedro Afonso de Aguiar to Calicut in advance, with the warning that he had come to settle scores for the mistreatment of Cabral and to get compensation for the overrunning of the Calicut factory in 1500.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In response, the Zamorin of Calicut sent back a string of messengers to Cannanore (and along the way to Calicut), each delivering promises that the Zamorin was willing to settle matters with Gama, and compensate the Portuguese for the loss of their factory goods.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 29, 1502 – Gama's large armada finally arrives before the harbor of Calicut (*Calecute*, Kozhikode).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin dispatches an emissary, a Brahmin (dressed as a Christian friar) on a boat to Gama.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama is angered, feeling that the Zamorin has changed his tone from his earlier messages, and demands the property taken from the factory be restored in full and brought to his ship, and that all Muslim merchants must be expelled from the Calicut, before any discussion about a treaty begins.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] While awaiting the Zamorin's reply, Gama seizes a nearby idling zambuq and some fishing boats that had unwisely ventured into Calicut harbor, taking some fifty fisherman captive.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] This action evidently angers the Zamorin, who sends a stern reply to Gama, noting that Gama had already taken severalfold times more property from Calicut ships, and slaughtered ten times more of his citizens (on the *Miri*, etc.) than the Portuguese lost in the 1500 riot.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Despite being the net sufferer and the clamor of his citizens for revenge, the Zamorin is prepared to forgive and forget and start anew.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin also replies that Calicut is a free port and he has no intention of expelling 'the Moors'.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] October 31, 1502 – Infuriated by the reply, Gama sends out a strongly worded ultimatum, declaring that the Zamorin's permission means nothing to him, that he has until noon the next day to deliver the Portuguese factory goods to his ship.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama uses this overnight interlude to send his boats out to sound the harbor of Calicut to find optimal firing positions.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] That same night, Calicut forces set about frantically digging entrenchments, erecting a protective timber palisade and laying cannon along the harbor shore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 1, 1502 – At noon, having received no reply, Gama orders that his Malabari prisoners be strung up by their necks from the shipmasts, allocating a few to each ship.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Calicut crowds approach the beach to watch the grisly spectacle.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Then the armada advances into the harbor and opens fire.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The bombardment is principally aimed at clearing the beach and trenches.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Malabari shore cannons are too few, their range and power too weak, to provide an effective reply.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The bombardment continues until nightfall.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] That night, the corpses of the hung Malabaris are taken from masts, their feet and hands severed off and sent by a small boat to the beach, with an insulting message to the Zamorin, including a demand that the Zamorin reimburse the Portuguese for the powder and shot expended on destroying his city.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 2, 1502 – The city bombardment resumes the next morning.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The mostly poor dwellings on the shore having been razed the previous day, the Portuguese cannons now have a clear view of central city and the statelier homes of the richer citizens of Calicut and bring their larger ordnance to bear.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The city is relentlessly bombarded all morning – some 400 large rounds and an indeterminate number from the smaller caliber guns At noon, when the Portuguese pause for lunch, a small group of Malabari vessels tries to attack the idling squad, but are quickly seen off.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 3, 1502 – Barros reports that the two-day bombardment had sufficiently crippled the city that several of the captains urge Gama to authorize a landing of troops to sack Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Gama, still hopeful the Zamorin might come to terms, turns down their request, believing a sack would only escalate matters to the point of no return.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] So, the next morning, vengeance satisfied, Gama sets sail out of Calicut harbor.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Seizing the convoy, Gama orders the cargoes transferred, the crews tied, their teeth beaten out, their noses and hands cut off and the ships set alight.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The violent treatment meted out by Vasco da Gama sends shockwaves throughout the Malabar coast.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Merchant ships in Indian ports hurriedly leave the area or go into concealment.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] All shipping along the coast essentially freezes.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Before leaving Calicut, Gama assembles a squadron of five or six fighting ships under Vicente Sodré and his brother Brás Sodré, with some 200 soldiers (mainly crossbowmen), to maintain the blockade on Calicut harbor, and patrol the coast preying on Calicut shipping.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The exact composition of the patrol squadron differs in the sources, and it seems there is some reshuffling of captains in the process.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The patrol squadron captains are taken from the lists in Castanheda, Góis and Osório Other sources are not so explicit.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The ship names are tentatively deduced from Gaspar Correia, who, as usual, deviates in naming the captains.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 3, 1502, His blockade of Calicut in place, Vasco da Gama arrives in Cochin (*Cohim*, Kochi) with the bulk of the armada.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He is received by Trimumpara ruler of Cochin, not without a touch of anxiety.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Nair hostage taken accidentally by the 2nd Armada the previous year is delivered, along with the letter of the other Nair who stayed back in Lisbon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama concludes negotiates a new commercial treaty with the ruler of Cochin, this time with a fixed-price schedule, like at Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Diogo Fernandes Correia, the new designated factor for Cochin, relieves Cabral's factor Gonçalo Gil Barbosa (now slated to be transferred to Cannanore).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They promptly set about their business of buying spices and loading ships in Cochin for the return journey.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] While conducting business at Cochin, Vasco da Gama receives a letter from the queen-regent of Quilon (*Coulão*, Kollam), on behalf of her young son, the raja Govardhana Martanda.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The queen invites the Portuguese fleet to load up with spices at Quilon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama declines politely, noting that he cannot do anything without the permission of his Cochinese hosts.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As a result, the queen-regent dispatches a messenger to the prince of Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Trimumpara Raja prevaricates at first, fearing that competition from Quilon's more amply supplied markets will hurt his own.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Cochin's slender supply is worrying the Portuguese factors.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] At length, an agreement is reached between all parties: Gama is to dispatch only two ships to load up with spices at Quilon, and promises not to set up a permanent factory in that city.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The two ships, carrying temporary factor João de Sá Pereira, the first Portuguese to enter Quilon, will load up quickly, and return to Cochin within ten days.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] November 19, 1502 – While at Cochin, Gama receives a message from Syrian Christian community of nearby Cranganore offering to place themselves under the protection of the King of Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama accepts their gift of a red silver-tipped sceptre, a symbolic command staff, but notes that he personally cannot do much, as he will be leaving soon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But he promises that the community can call on the Portuguese naval patrol of Vicente Sodré at any time, should they need anything.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] January 3, 1503 – A wealthy Brahmin, accompanied by his son and nephew, shows up Cochin and requests permission from Vasco da Gama to take passage on the 4th Armada to Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama assures him he is fully empowered by the king, at which point the Brahmin then offers to mediate a peace treaty between Gama and the Zamorin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama agrees, and the Brahmin returns to Calicut, coming back to Cochin shortly after accompanied by a Nair of the Zamorin's household, with a concrete offer to compensate the Portuguese for the goods lost in the Calicut factory.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It seems a fair offer, so Gama decides to personally finalize the arrangement.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] January 5, 1503 – Vasco da Gama takes his cousin's ship, the *Frol de la Mar*, plus one caravel, to carry the Brahmin and the Nair back to Calicut, to finalize the peace treaty with the Zamorin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama leaves the rest of the 4th Armada in Cochin under D.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] (Rumors of the imminent peace with Calicut angers the merchants of Cochin, who feel they will be short-changed by any agreement with Calicut; Coutinho has a difficult time securing the continued purchasing and loading of spices).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama is taking only a light escort, but he imagines Vicente Sodré is in the vicinity and will provide additional security.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] However, as it happens, Vicente Sodré had left Calicut a few days earlier.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He had been maintaining a continuous blockade on Calicut harbor, and engaging in repeated cat-and-mouse chases with small Calicut fishing ships that dared venture out.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] At one point, Sodré gave a couple of fishing boats chase into a side-channel, and sailed into a trap – forty armed Calicut paraus quickly surrounded him.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] A lucky cannon shot on the lead ship broke up the ambush, allowing Sodré to extricate himself from there quickly.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He sailed out and raced back to Cannanore to pick up the rest of his patrol.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama arrives in Calicut harbor during this absence, unaware of any of this.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Seeing no sign of Sodré, Gama orders the escort caravel to go towards Cannanore to find him.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He anchors his own ship, the large *Flor de la Mar*, inside the harbor and lowers a skiff to take the Brahmin to shore, to meet the Zamorin and arrange for the delivery of the compensation payment, retaining the Brahmin's two relatives and the Nair on board as hostages.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Three days are spent waiting, the Brahmin shuttling back and forth between the ship and the shore repeatedly to report and consult on the progress of the negotiations.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] All seemed to be going well, but in the early morning hours of the fourth day, however, a hundred armed zambuks and paraus swarm into the harbor from the nearby channels and quickly surround the *Flor de la Mar*.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The *Flor'*s high sides do not allow the Portuguese to respond with artillery – the ship's cannons are mounted too high and the paraus are too close for an angle of shot, so the crew turns desperately to crossbows, musket fire and heaving rocks to keep them at bay.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Days before the encounter, Gama had captured a large parau, which was now tied to the stern of the *Flor*.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In the heat of the fighting, Malabari sappers row up to the tied parau, fill it with tinder, set it afire, and direct the flaming ship towards the *Flor*.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama immediately orders the cables cut and the flames of the drifting parau only just miss them.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Throughout all this, some of the Portuguese sailors are desperately trying to cut the cables on the anchor – a process that took time, as Gama had ordered it down with an iron chain.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But eventually the anchor is cut, and the *Flor* begins to sail away.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] As distance is gained from the zambuks and paraus, the ship's cannons can now come into play and fire on the pursuers.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The *Flor* reaches the mouth of the harbor just as Vicente Sodré arrives back from Cannanore with three caravels.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Seeing the ambush is foiled, the Calicut boats turn around and slip back into the side-channels of the harbor.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Before leaving Calicut, Gama orders the three hostages – the son & nephew of the Brahmin and the Nair – strung up by their necks on the main mast, in full view of the city of Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He dispatches their corpses on a raft to the shore, pinned with a note swearing revenge on the Zamorin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] After the ambush, Gama, escorted by Sodré's patrol returns to Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The assembled Calicut fleet is estimated at 20 large ships, 40 gun-mounted *sambuks* (large dhows) and an innumerable number of smaller oar-powered paraus, carrying several thousand armed men.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Trimumpara Raja of Cochin urges Gama to avoid the fleet and just set sail for Portugal at once.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vasco da Gama refuses to revise his plans.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He needs to return to Cannanore to deposit the factor Barbosa there and pick up a cargo of ginger he had ordered.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] And he was itching for revenge for the ambush.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They are soon joined by Sodré's caravel squadron, and set sail warily towards Cannanore, guns ready for the Calicut ambush.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama and Sodré spot the Calicut fleet of Coja Casem and Arab privateer Cojambar, near the coast, out of Calicut harbor.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Although the Arab squadron is out of commission too soon, Coja Casem nonetheless proceeds forward with his fleet of Malabari sambuks, hoping to use their speed to outmaneuver the guns of the heavy-laden naus and reach for the grapple.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Gama sends the escort caravels under Vicente Sodré to intercept them in their tracks, while the cargo naus hurry on toward Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Although the caravels are outnumbered, it is not much of a battle.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The fight is essentially over when Pero Rafael and Gil Matoso quickly board and capture Coja Casem's flagship (oddly, found with a lot of women and children on board).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Calicut fleet breaks up and rushes back to port.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The pursuing caravels capture a number of sambuks, which they proceed to tow and set on fire before Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The long-prepared ambush has been foiled.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Danger dispelled, the caravels proceed to Cannanore to make junction with the main fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Battle of Calicut, like the previous year's naval battle of Cannanore, once again demonstrated the critical importance of the technical superiority of Portuguese ships and naval artillery.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But it also demonstrated to the Portuguese that the Zamorin of Calicut was not as easy to intimidate as they had expected.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Despite the terror actions, the bombardment and the naval blockade, the Zamorin steadfastly refused to capitulate to Vasco da Gama's terms.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] On the contrary, the hiring of an Arab privateer fleet demonstrated a certain resourcefulness and willingness to continue fighting and take the fight to the Portuguese.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The hiring of Cojambar was also a foreboding.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin clearly understood he had to appeal to foreigners to help close the technical gap between Indian and Portuguese forces.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Surely it would only be a matter of time before the Zamorin got his hands on Arab, Turkish and Venetian technology, and more substantial support from these great powers than just a Red Sea pirate or two?
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] If the battle of Calicut impressed something on Vasco da Gama, it was precisely that the Portuguese in India were living on borrowed time, that it was going to take more resources than he had to bring the Zamorin to heel and secure continued Portuguese access to the spice markets.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] And that was the message he would bring back to Lisbon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In the meantime, his priority was to do everything he could to maintain the Portuguese toe in India - that is, to protect the Portuguese factories and Indian allies of Cochin and Cannanore, from the Zamorin's inevitable revenge the moment the 4th Armada left.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Arriving in Cannanore, Gama leaves Cabral's old factor Gonçalo Gil Barbosa, and two assistants, Bastião Álvares and Diogo Nunes.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] With the permission of the Kolithiri Raja of Cannanore, Gama erects a small palisade around the factory.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Some 200 armed men (others report merely 20) are to remain with the factory.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] More troubling, however, is the India patrol squadron.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Back in Lisbon, Vicente Sodré had been given a commission (*regimento*) by king Manuel I of Portugal instructing him to lead a patrol of five or six caravels in the Gulf of Aden, and prey on the rich Arab prizes going in and out of the Red Sea.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vasco da Gama, realizing the vulnerability of Cochin and Cannanore, invokes rank as captain-major of the armada and orders Sodré to set that mission aside, and maintain his patrol on the Indian coast, to defend the Portuguese factories and their Indian allies against any reaction by the Zamorin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The return journey is quick and relatively smooth, with only one stop in Mozambique Island.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It is caught in a slight storm around the Cape, where Estêvão da Gama's *Flor da la Mar* parts company from the rest.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Estêvão da Gama, making his way back to Lisbon by himself, is said to have stumbled upon the South Atlantic islands of Saint Helena (already discovered the previous year by João da Nova's Third Armada).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vasco da Gama's main fleet arrives in Lisbon in September, 1503.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama delivers his report, noting his failure to bring the Zamorin of Calicut to terms, and urging the immediate outfitting of a strong fleet to establish strong permanent Portuguese garrisons to protect the allied cities of Cochin and Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Gama arrives too late to affect the outfitting of the 5th Armada, which had already departed in April, 1503 under the command of Afonso de Albuquerque.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But his recommendation will guide the formation of the next one, the 6th Armada, set to sail in the Spring of 1504 under the command of Lopo Soares de Albergaria.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] March, 1503 – As soon as Vasco da Gama's 4th Armada leaves India, as predicted, Raja Trimumpara of Cochin receives intelligence that the Zamorin of Calicut is at this very moment preparing a landward invasion of Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Portuguese factor Diogo Fernandes Correia urges Vicente Sodré to keep the caravel patrol squadron close to Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Vicente Sodré, eager for the easy plunder of the Arab Red Sea shipping, dismisses the rumors, Correia reminds him of Gama's orders, to no avail – Sodré pulls out his old royal *regimento* and orders the coastal patrol to follow him out to the Red Sea.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] It is said that at least two of the captains of the coastal patrol refuse Sodré's orders, and willingly surrender the command of their ships rather than disobey Gama's original orders.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The composition of the patrol that set out to the Red Sea varies in different accounts.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] One arrangement is that it was six ships: 1.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vicente Sodré first sets out north to Gujarat, where it captures a great merchant ship off Chaul.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The patrol then sails west into the Gulf of Aden, at the mouth of the Red Sea, to catch more prizes.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] About five Arab merchant ships are seized by the patrol there but, according to the account written later by Pêro de Ataíde, the Sodré brothers set about claiming a disproportionate share of the plunder for themselves, including embezzling the royal fifth.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In Ataíde's account, Brás Sodré appears as the villain of the story.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Already unhappy at the decision to abandon their comrades in India, the patrol captains quarreled with the Sodré brothers and nearly mutinied.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In late April, the patrol anchored in at Kuria Muria islands (off the coast of Oman).
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The local inhabitants warned them that a seasonal tempest was forming and that they had better move their ships to a safer shelter on the southern side of the island.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Four patrol captains moved their ships accordingly, but Vicente Sodré and Brás Sodré refused (the ongoing quarrel over the spoils may have been a factor in this decision.) As the locals predicted, the tempest came, destroyed and sunk the ships of Vicente Sodré and Brás Sodré.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Mearns of BWR and Oman's Ministry of Heritage and Culture.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] In the aftermath, the four remaining ships of the coastal patrol, who elected of Pêro de Ataíde as their new commander, set back for India.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] However, contrary winds make it a difficult journey, and they inch back only painfully and slowly.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The battered patrol hobbles into Angediva island sometime in the summer of 1503, where they are forced to stop to repair their crippled ships.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Four days after arriving in Angediva, a fifth ship, the caravel of António do Campo (who having missed the previous year's monsoon, was forced to stay in East Africa throughout all this) arrives in Anjediva and joins the patrol.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] They are still repairing at Angediva when the ships of Francisco de Albuquerque and Nicolau Coelho, the vanguard of the 5th Armada, arrives in India in August, 1503.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] April 1503 – Not long after the Sodré patrol departed for the Red Sea, the Zamorin of Calicut arrived with his 50,000-strong army at *Repelim* (Edapalli), on the boundaries of the Cochinese state.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] He demanded that the Raja Trimumpara of Cochin hand his Portuguese guests over to him.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] But Trimumpara refused and his son Narayan repels two Calicut assaults.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] By bribery and deceit, the Zamorin manages to detach a lot of Cochin's army, overwhelms the defenses and kills prince Narayan at a battle near the Edapalli ford.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Trimumpara Raja and his Portuguese guests (factor Diogo Fernandes Correia and his assistants), accompanied by a small loyal Nair guard, abandon Cochin city and flee across the harbor to Vypin, a barrier island of the Vembanad lagoon.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Vypin's natural defenses and the deteriorating weather prevent the Zamorin from launching assault boats and seizing the island.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Frustrated, the Zamorin burns down the city of Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The siege will drag on for several months, until Francisco de Albuquerque, leading the remnant of the Sodré patrol, hurrying down from Angediva, arrived in Cochin in August–September, and forced the Calicut forces to withdraw.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] Expert gun-founders, the Italians will teach Calicut to found large European guns and help close the technological gap between Indian and Portuguese artillery.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin of Calicut, before burning down Cochin, removed an ancient sacred stone, upon which the ancient Kings of Malabar (see Chera Dynasty) were traditionally ceremonially esconsed as lords of the sea and overlords of all the Malabari states.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The sacred stone had originally been housed at the ancient Malabari capital of Cranganore, but had since been moved to Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/4th-portuguese-india-armada-gama-1502-p02] The Zamorin now moved it once more, to Edapalli.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The word *admiral* in Middle English comes from Anglo-French *amiral*, "commander", from Medieval Latin *admiralis*, *admirallus*.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The 1818 edition of Samuel Johnson's *A Dictionary of the English Language*, edited and revised by the Rev.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The quote from John Minsheu's Dictionarie in Spanish and English (1599), given in Johnson's Dictionary, has been confirmed as being accurate.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] Those Phanariots who attained the princely position of dragoman of the fleet served under the Ottoman admiral having administration of the Aegean islands and the Anatolian coast.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] Central Command, introduced Vice Admiral Mark I.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] One alternate etymology proposes that the term admiral evolved, instead, from the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ (أمير الأمراء).
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] Under the reign of the Buyid dynasty (934 to 1062) of Iraq and Iran, the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ, which means prince of princes, came to denote the heir-apparent, or crown prince.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] This alternate etymology states that the term was in use for the Greco-Arab naval leaders (e.g.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] Christodulus) in the Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture of Norman Sicily, which had formerly been ruled by Arabs, at least by the early 11th century.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] During this time, the Norman Roger II of Sicily (1095–1154) employed a Greek Christian, known as George of Antioch, who previously had served as a naval commander for several North African Muslim rulers.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] Roger styled George in Abbasid fashion as *Amir of Amirs*, or Amīr al-Umarāʾ, with the title becoming Latinized in the 13th century as *ammiratus ammiratorum*.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The Sicilians and later the Genoese took the first two parts of the term from their Aragon opponents and used them as one word, *amiral*. .
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The French gave their sea commanders similar titles while in Portuguese and Spanish the word changed to *almirante*.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] As the word was used by people speaking Latin or Latin-based languages it gained the "d" and endured a series of different endings and spellings leading to the English spelling *admyrall* in the 14th century and to *admiral* by the 16th century.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The etymology of a word does not suggest the antiquity of the word as it may have appeared in other languages with entirely different pronunciations.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The Greek ναύαρχος, for instance, which is pronounced "naúarkhos", existed from very ancient times in Greece.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The word "admiral" has come to be almost exclusively associated with the highest naval rank in most of the world's navies, equivalent to the army rank of general.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] However, this was not always the case; for example, in some European countries prior to the end of World War II, admiral was the third highest naval rank after general admiral and grand admiral.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The rank of admiral has also been subdivided into various grades, several of which are historically extinct while others remain in use in most present-day navies.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The Royal Navy used the colours red, white, and blue, in descending order to indicate seniority of its admirals until 1864; for example, Horatio Nelson's highest rank was vice-admiral of the white.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] The generic term for these naval equivalents of army generals is flag officer.
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] Some navies have also used army-type titles for them, such as the Cromwellian "general at sea".
[src:line-of-battle/admiral] While the rank is used in most of NATO countries, it is ranked differently depending on the country.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The **Admiralty** was a department of the Kingdom of Great Britain and from 1801 of the Government of the United Kingdom that was responsible for the command of the Royal Navy.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Historically, its titular head was the Lord High Admiral – one of the Great Officers of State.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] For much of its history, from the early 18th century until its abolition, the role of the Lord High Admiral was almost invariably put "in commission" and exercised by the Lords Commissioner of the Admiralty, who sat on the governing Board of Admiralty, rather than by a single person.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was replaced by the Admiralty Board in 1964, as part of the reforms that created the Ministry of Defence and its Navy Department (later Navy Command).
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was among the most important departments of the British Government, because of the Royal Navy's role in the expansion and maintenance of the English overseas possessions in the 17th century, the British Empire in the 18th century, and subsequently.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The modern Admiralty Board, to which the functions of the Admiralty were transferred in 1964, is a committee of the tri-service Defence Council of the United Kingdom.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] This Admiralty Board meets only twice a year, and the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy is controlled by a Navy Board (not to be confused with the historic Navy Board).
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] It is common for the various authorities now in charge of the Royal Navy to be referred to as simply 'The Admiralty'.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Since 1964, the title of Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom has been vested in the monarch; the title was awarded to Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh by Queen Elizabeth II on his 90th birthday in 2011 and remained with him until his death in 2021.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] There also continues to be a Vice-Admiral of the United Kingdom and a Rear-Admiral of the United Kingdom, both of which are honorary offices.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Admiral of England (later Lord Admiral, and later Lord High Admiral) was created around 1400; there had previously been Admirals of the northern and western seas.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Henry VIII established the Council of the Marine—later to become the Navy Board—in 1546, to oversee administrative affairs of the naval service.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Operational control of the Royal Navy remained the responsibility of the Lord High Admiral, who was one of the nine Great Officers of State.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] This management approach would continue in force in the Royal Navy until 1832.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Charles I put the office of Lord High Admiral into commission in 1628, and control of the Royal Navy passed to a committee in the form of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Lord High Admiral passed a number of times in and out of commission until 1709, after which the office was almost permanently in commission (the last Lord High Admiral being the future King William IV in the early 19th century).
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] These principal officers came to be known as the Navy Board responsible for 'civil administration' of the navy, from 1546 to 1832.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] This structure of administering the navy lasted for 285 years, however, the supply system was often inefficient and corrupt its deficiencies were due as much to its limitations of the times they operated in.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The various functions within the Admiralty were not coordinated effectively and lacked inter-dependency with each other, with the result that in 1832, Sir James Graham abolished the Navy Board and merged its functions within those of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] At the time this had distinct advantages; however, it failed to retain the principle of distinctions between the Admiralty and supply, and a lot of bureaucracy followed with the merger.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1860 saw big growth in the development of technical crafts, the expansion of more admiralty branches that really began with age of steam that would have an enormous influence on the navy and naval thought.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Between 1860 and 1908, there was no real study of strategy and of staff work conducted within the naval service; it was practically ignored.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] All the Navy's talent flowed to the great technical universities.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] This school of thought for the next 50 years was exclusively technically based.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The first serious attempt to introduce a sole management body to administer the naval service manifested itself in the creation of the Admiralty Navy War Council in 1909.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Following this, a new advisory body called the Admiralty War Staff was then instituted in 1912, headed by the Chief of the War Staff who was responsible for administering three new sub-divisions responsible for operations, intelligence and mobilisation.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The new War Staff had hardly found its feet and it continually struggled with the opposition to its existence by senior officers they were categorically opposed to a staff.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The deficiencies of the system within this government department could be seen in the conduct of the Dardanelles campaign.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] There were no mechanisms in place to answer the big strategic questions.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Sir John Jellicoe came to the Admiralty in 1916.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] He reorganised the war staff as following: Chief of War Staff, Operations, Intelligence, Signal Section, Mobilisation, Trade.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was not until 1917 that the admiralty department was again properly reorganised and began to function as a professional military staff.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] In May 1917, the term "Admiralty War Staff" was renamed and that department and its functional role were superseded by a new "Admiralty Naval Staff"; in addition, the newly created office of Chief of the Naval Staff was merged in the office of the First Sea Lord.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Also appointed was a new post, that of Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff, and an Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff; all were given seats on the Board of Admiralty.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] This for the first time gave the naval staff direct representation on the board; the presence of three senior naval senior members on the board ensured the necessary authority to carry through any operation of war.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Deputy Chief of Naval Staff would direct all operations and movements of the fleet, while the Assistant Chief of Naval Staff would be responsible for mercantile movements and anti-submarine operations.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Controller would be re-established to deal with all questions relating to supply; on 6 September 1917, a Deputy First Sea Lord, was added to the Board who would administer operations abroad and deal with questions of foreign policy.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] In October 1917, the development of the staff was carried one step further by the creation of two sub-committees of the Board—the Operations Committee and the Maintenance Committee.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Lord of the Admiralty was chairman of both committees, and the Operations Committee consisted of the First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff, the Deputy First Sea Lord, Assistant Chief of Naval Staff, and Fifth Sea Lord.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Full operational control of the Royal Navy was finally handed over to the Chief of Naval Staff (CNS) by an order in Council, effective October 1917, under which he became responsible for the issuing of orders affecting all war operations directly to the fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] It also empowered the CNS to issue orders in their own name, as opposed to them previously being issued by the Permanent Secretary of the Admiralty in the name of the Board.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1964, the Admiralty—along with the War Office and the Air Ministry—were abolished as separate departments of state, and placed under one single new Ministry of Defence.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Within the expanded Ministry of Defence are the new Admiralty Board which has a separate Navy Board responsible for the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy, the Army Board and the Air Force Board, each headed by the Secretary of State for Defence.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] In order to deliver this the Naval Staff was organised into specialist Divisions and Sections.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] When the Admiralty unified with the Ministry of Defence in 1964 they were re designated as Directorates of the Naval Staff.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty Departments, which provides the men, ships, aircraft and supplies to carry out the approved policy.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The departments are superintended by the various offices of the Sea Lords.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Department of the Permanent Secretary which was the general co-ordinating agency, regulating naval finance, providing advice on policy, conducing all correspondence on behalf of the Board and maintaining admiralty records.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its primary component to deliver this is the Admiralty Secretariat, sections of the Secretariat (other than those which provide Common Services) were known as Branches.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Board of Admiralty consisted of a number of Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners were always a mixture of admirals, known as Naval Lords or Sea Lords and Civil Lords, normally politicians.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The quorum of the Board was two commissioners and a secretary.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The president of the Board was known as the First Lord of the Admiralty, who was a member of the Cabinet.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] After 1806, the First Lord of the Admiralty was always a civilian, while the professional head of the navy came to be (and is still today) known as the First Sea Lord.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty were the members of The Board of Admiralty, which exercised the office of Lord High Admiral when it was not vested in a single person.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The commissioners were a mixture of politicians without naval experience and professional naval officers, the proportion of naval officers generally increasing over time.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff was the Chief Naval Adviser on the Board of Admiralty to the First Lord and superintended the offices of the sea lords and the admiralty naval staff.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was an independent board from 1546 until 1628 when it became subordinate to, yet autonomous of the Board of Admiralty until 1832.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its principal commissioners of the Navy advised the board in relation to civil administration of the naval affairs.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was based at the Navy Office.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Additional Civil Lord of the Admiralty.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Parliamentary and Financial Secretary to the Admiralty.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] It evolved from *Admiralty Navy War Council, (1909–1912) which in turn became the Admiralty War Staff, (1912–1917) before finally becoming the Admiralty Naval Staff in 1917.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was the former senior command, operational planning, policy and strategy department within the British Admiralty.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Vice Chief of the Naval Staff.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] Offices of the Assistant Chiefs of the Naval Staff.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Secretary's Department consisted of members of the civil service it was directed and controlled by a senior civil servant Permanent Secretary to the Board of Admiralty he was not a Lord Commissioner of the Admiralty, he functioned as a member of the board, and attended all of its meetings.
[src:line-of-battle/admiralty-united-kingdom] In some cases, the term *admiralty* is used in a wider sense, as meaning *sea power* or *rule over the seas*, rather than in strict reference to the institution exercising such power.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque advanced the three-fold Portuguese grand scheme of combating Islam, spreading Christianity, and securing the trade of spices by establishing a Portuguese Asian empire.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Among his achievements, Albuquerque managed to conquer Goa and was the first European of the Renaissance to raid the Persian Gulf, and he led the first voyage by a European fleet into the Red Sea.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was appointed head of the "fleet of the Arabian and Persian sea" in 1506.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Many of the conflicts in which he was directly involved took place in the Indian Ocean, in the Persian Gulf regions for control of the trade routes, and on the coasts of India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] His military brilliance in these initial campaigns enabled Portugal to become the first global empire in history.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He led the Portuguese forces in numerous battles, including the conquest of Goa in 1510 and the capture of Malacca in 1511.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] During the last five years of his life, he turned to administration, where his actions as the second governor of Portuguese India were crucial to the longevity of the Portuguese Empire.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He oversaw expeditions that resulted in establishing diplomatic contacts with the Ayutthaya Kingdom through his envoy Duarte Fernandes, with Pegu in Myanmar, and Timor and the Moluccas through a voyage headed by António de Abreu and Francisco Serrão.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He laid the path for European trade with Ming China through Rafael Perestrello.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He also aided in establishing diplomatic relations with Ethiopia, and established diplomatic ties with Persia during the Safavid dynasty.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Throughout his career, he received epithets such as "the Terrible", "the Great", "the Lion of the Seas", "the Portuguese Mars", and "the Caesar of the East".
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso de Albuquerque was born in 1453 in Alhandra, near Lisbon.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was the second son of Gonçalo de Albuquerque, Lord of Vila Verde dos Francos, and Dona Leonor de Menezes.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] His father held an important position at court and was connected by remote illegitimate descent with the Portuguese monarchy.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was a descendant of King Denis's illegitimate son, Afonso Sanches, Lord of Albuquerque.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was educated in mathematics and Latin at the court of Afonso V of Portugal, where he befriended Prince John, the future King John II of Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1471, under the command of Afonso V, he was present at the conquest of Tangier and Arzila in Morocco, and he served there as an officer for some years.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1476, he accompanied Prince John in wars against Castile, including the Battle of Toro.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He participated in the campaign on the Italian peninsula in 1480 to assist Ferdinand I of Naples in repelling the Ottoman invasion of Otranto.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On his return in 1481, when John was crowned as King John II, Albuquerque was made master of the horse and chief equerry (**estribeiro-mor**) to the king, a post which he held throughout John's reign.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1489, he returned to military campaigning in North Africa, as commander of defense in the Graciosa fortress, an island in the river Luco near the city of Larache.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1490 Albuquerque was part of the guard of John II.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He returned to Arzila in 1495, where his younger brother Martim died fighting by his side.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] When King Manuel I of Portugal ascended to the throne following the death of his cousin John II, he held a cautious attitude towards Albuquerque, who was a close friend of his predecessor and seventeen years Manuel's senior.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Eight years later, on 6 April 1503 Albuquerque was sent on his first expedition to India together with his cousin Francisco de Albuquerque.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Each commanded three ships, sailing with Duarte Pacheco Pereira and Nicolau Coelho.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] They engaged in several battles against the forces of the Zamorin of Calicut (*Calecute*, Kozhikode) and succeeded in establishing the king of Cochin (*Cochim*, Kochi) securely on his throne.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In return, the king of Cochin gave the Portuguese permission to build the Portuguese fort *Immanuel* (Fort Kochi) and establish trade relations with Quilon (*Coulão*, Kollam).
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] This laid the foundation for the eastern Portuguese Empire.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque returned home in July 1504 and was well received by King Manuel I.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After he assisted with the creation of a strategy for the Portuguese efforts in the east, King Manuel entrusted him with the command of a squadron of five vessels in the fleet of sixteen sailing for India in early 1506, headed by Tristão da Cunha.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The aim of the expedition was to conquer Socotra and build a fortress there, hoping to close the trade in the Red Sea.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque went as "chief-captain for the Coast of Arabia", sailing under da Cunha's orders until reaching Mozambique.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He carried a sealed letter with a secret mission ordered by the king: after fulfilling the first mission, he was to replace the first viceroy of India, Francisco de Almeida, whose term ended two years later.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Before departing, he legitimized his son Brás ("Braz" in the old Portuguese spelling), born to a common Portuguese woman named Joana Vicente in 1500.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque piloted his ship himself, having lost his appointed pilot on departure.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In Mozambique Channel, they rescued Captain João da Nova, who had encountered difficulties on his return from India; da Nova and his ship, the *Flor de la mar*, joined da Cunha's fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] From Malindi, da Cunha sent envoys to Ethiopia, which at the time was thought to be closer to India than it actually is, under the aegis of Albuquerque.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After failing to reach Ethiopia, he managed to land the envoys in Filuk.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After successful attacks on Arab cities on the East African coast, the expedition conquered the island of Socotra and built a fortress at Suq, hoping to establish a base to stop the Red Sea commerce to the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] However, Socotra was abandoned four years later, as it was eventually realised to be a poor location for a base.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] At Socotra, they parted ways: Tristão da Cunha sailed for India, where he would relieve the Portuguese besieged at Cannanore, while Afonso took seven ships and 500 men to Ormuz in the Persian Gulf, one of the chief eastern centers of commerce.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On his way, he conquered the cities of Curiati (Kuryat), Muscat in July 1507, and Khor Fakkan, accepting the submission of the cities of Kalhat and Sohar.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He arrived at Hormuz on 25 September and soon captured the city, which agreed to become a tributary state of the Portuguese king.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Ormuz was then a tributary state of Shah Ismail I (r.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In a famous episode, shortly after its conquest, Albuquerque was confronted by Persian envoys, who demanded the payment of the due tribute from him instead.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He ordered them to be given a stock of cannonballs, arrows and weapons, retorting that "such was the currency struck in Portugal to pay the tribute demanded from the dominions of King Manuel".
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] According to Brás de Albuquerque, it was Shah Ismael who first addressed Albuquerque as "Lion of the seas".
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso began building the Fort of Our Lady of Victory (later renamed Fort of Our Lady of the Conception) on Hormuz Island, engaging his men of all ranks in the work.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] However, some of his officers, claiming that Afonso was exceeding his orders, revolted against the heavy work and climate and departed for India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] With his fleet reduced to two ships and left without supplies, he was unable to maintain his position.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In January 1508, he was forced to abandon Ormuz.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He raided coastal villages to resupply the settlement of Socotra, returned to Ormuz, and then headed to India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso arrived at Cannanore on the Malabar coast in December 1508, where he opened the sealed letter that he had received from the king before the viceroy, Dom Francisco de Almeida, which named him as governor to succeed Almeida.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The viceroy, supported by the officers who had abandoned Afonso at Ormuz, had a matching royal order but declined to yield.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He protested that his term ended only in January and stated his intention to avenge his son's death by fighting the Mamluk fleet of Mirocem, refusing Afonso's offer to fight the Mamluk fleet himself.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso avoided confrontation, which could have led to civil war, and moved to Kochi, India, to await further instruction from the king.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Increasingly isolated, he wrote to Diogo Lopes de Sequeira, who arrived in India with a new fleet, but was ignored as Sequeira joined Almeida.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] At the same time, Afonso refused approaches from opponents of Almeida who encouraged him to seize power.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 3 February 1509, Almeida fought the naval Battle of Diu against a joint fleet of Mamluks, Ottomans, the Zamorin of Calicut, and the Sultan of Gujarat.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] His victory was decisive: the Ottomans and Mamluks abandoned the Indian Ocean, easing the way for Portuguese rule there for the next century.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In August, after a petition from Afonso's former officers with the support of Diogo Lopes de Sequeira claiming him unfit for governance, Afonso was sent in custody to St.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] There he remained under what he considered as imprisonment.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso was released after three months' confinement, on the arrival at Cannanore of the Marshal of Portugal Fernando Coutinho with a large fleet sent by the king.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Coutinho was the most important Portuguese noble to visit India up to that point.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He brought an armada of fifteen ships and 3,000 men to defend Afonso's rights, and to take Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 4 November 1509, Afonso became the second Governor of Portuguese India, a position he would hold until his death.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Almeida set off to return to Portugal, but he was killed before he got there in a skirmish with the Khoekhoe.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Upon his assuming office, Afonso intended to dominate the Muslim world and control the spice trade.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Initially, King Manuel I and his council in Lisbon tried to distribute the power by outlining three areas of jurisdiction in the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1509, the nobleman Diogo Lopes de Sequeira was sent with a fleet to Southeast Asia, to seek an agreement with Sultan Mahmud Shah of Malacca, but failed and returned to Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] To Jorge de Aguiar was given the region between the Cape of Good Hope and Gujarat.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was succeeded by Duarte de Lemos, but left for Cochin and then for Portugal, leaving his fleet to Afonso.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In January 1510, obeying the orders from the king and aware of the absence of the Zamorin, Afonso advanced on Calicut.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The attack was initially successful, but unravelled when Marshal Coutinho, infuriated by Albuquerque's success against Calicut and desiring glory for himself, attacked the Zamorin's palace against Albuquerque's advice, and was ambushed.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] During the retreat, Afonso was badly wounded and was forced to flee to the ships, barely escaping with his life, while Coutinho was killed.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Soon after the failed attack, Afonso assembled a fleet of 23 ships and 1200 men.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Contemporary reports state that he wanted to fight the Egyptian Mamluk Sultanate fleet in the Red Sea or return to Hormuz.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] However, he had been informed by Timoji (a privateer in the service of the Hindu Vijayanagara Empire) that it would be easier to fight them in Goa, where they had sheltered after the Battle of Diu, and also of the illness of the Sultan Yusuf Adil Shah, and war between the Deccan sultanates.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] So he relied on surprise in the capture of Goa from the Sultanate of Bijapur.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] A first assault took place in Goa from 4 March to 20 May 1510.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] His fleet was scattered, and a palace revolt in Kochi hindered his recovery, so he headed to Fort Anjediva.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] New ships arrived from Portugal, which were intended for the nobleman Diogo Mendes de Vasconcelos at Malacca, who had been given a rival command of the region.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Three months later, on 25 November Afonso reappeared at Goa with a renovated fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Diogo Mendes de Vasconcelos was compelled to accompany him with the reinforcements for Malacca and about 300 Malabari reinforcements from Cannanore.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In less than a day, they took Goa from Ismail Adil Shah and his Ottoman allies, who surrendered on 10 December.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] It is estimated that 6000 of the 9000 Muslim defenders of the city died, either in the fierce battle in the streets or by drowning while trying to escape.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso regained the support of the Hindu population, although he frustrated the initial expectations of Timoji, who aspired to become governor.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso rewarded him by appointing him chief "Aguazil" of the city, an administrator and representative of the Hindu and Muslim people, as a knowledgeable interpreter of the local customs.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He then made an agreement to lower the yearly tribute.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In Goa, Afonso established the first Portuguese mint in the East, after Timoja's merchants had complained of the scarcity of currency, taking it as an opportunity to solidify the territorial conquest.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The new coin, based on the existing local coins, showed a cross on the obverse and an armillary sphere (or "esfera"), King Manuel's badge, on the reverse.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Gold cruzados or *manueis*, silver *esferas* and *alf-esferas*, and bronze "leais" were issued.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque founded at Goa the *Hospital Real de Goa* or Royal Hospital of Goa, by the Church of Santa Catarina.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Upon hearing that the doctors were extorting the sickly with excessive fees, Albuquerque summoned them, declaring that "You charge a physician's pay and don't know what disease the men who serve our lord the King suffer from.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Thus, I want to teach you what is it that they die from" and put them to work building the city walls all day till nightfall before releasing them.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite constant attacks, Goa became the center of Portuguese India, with the conquest triggering the compliance of neighbouring kingdoms: the Sultan of Gujarat and the Zamorin of Calicut sent embassies, offering alliances and local grants to fortify.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso then used Goa to secure the spice trade in favor of Portugal and sell Persian horses to Vijayanagara and Hindu princes in return for their assistance.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The King of Portugal has often commanded me to go to the Straits, because...this was the best place to intercept the trade which the Moslems...carry on in these parts.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] So it was to do Our Lord's service that we were brought here; by taking Malacca, we would close the Straits so that never again would the Moslems be able to bring their spices by this route....
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] I am very sure that, if this Malacca trade is taken out of their hands, Cairo and Mecca will be completely lost.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In February 1511, through a friendly Hindu merchant, Nina Chatu, Afonso received a letter from Rui de Araújo, one of the nineteen Portuguese held at Malacca since 1509.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] It urged moving forward with the largest possible fleet to demand their release, and gave details of the fortifications.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso showed it to Diogo Mendes de Vasconcelos, as an argument to advance as a joint fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In April 1511, after fortifying Goa, he gathered a force of about 900 Portuguese, 200 Hindu mercenaries and about eighteen ships.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He then sailed to Malacca against orders and despite the protest of Diogo Mendes, who claimed command of the expedition.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso eventually centralized the Portuguese government in the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After the Malaccan conquest, he wrote a letter to the king to explain his disagreement with Diogo Mendes, suggesting that further divisions could be harmful to the Portuguese in India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Under his command was Ferdinand Magellan, who had participated in the failed embassy of Diogo Lopes de Sequeira in 1509.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After a false start towards the Red Sea, they sailed to the Strait of Malacca.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] It was the richest city that the Portuguese tried to take, and a focal point in the trade network where Malay traders met Gujarati, Chinese, Japanese, Javanese, Bengali, Persian and Arabic, among others, described by Tomé Pires as of invaluable richness.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite its wealth, it was mostly a wooden-built city, with few masonry buildings but was defended by a mercenary force estimated at 20,000 men and more than 2000 pieces of artillery.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Its greatest weakness was the unpopularity of the government of Sultan Mahmud Shah, who favoured Muslims, arousing dissatisfaction amongst other merchants.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso made a bold approach to the city, his ships decorated with banners, firing cannon volleys.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He declared himself lord of all the navigation, demanded the Sultan release the prisoners and pay for damages, and demanded consent to build a fortified trading post.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The Sultan eventually freed the prisoners, but was unimpressed by the small Portuguese contingent.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso then burned some ships at the port and four coastal buildings as a demonstration.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The city being divided by the Malacca River, the connecting bridge was a strategic point, so at dawn on 25 July, the Portuguese landed and fought a tough battle, facing poisoned arrows, taking the bridge in the evening.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After fruitlessly waiting for the Sultan's reaction, they returned to the ships and prepared a junk (offered by Chinese merchants), filling it with men, artillery and sandbags.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Commanded by António de Abreu, it sailed upriver at high tide to the bridge.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After a fierce fight during which the Sultan appeared with an army of war elephants, the defenders were dispersed and the Sultan fled.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso waited for the reaction of the Sultan.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Merchants approached, asking for Portuguese protection.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] They were given banners to mark their premises, a sign that they would not be looted.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 15 August, the Portuguese attacked again, but the Sultan had fled the city.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Under strict orders, they looted the city, but respected the banners.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso prepared Malacca's defenses against a Malay counterattack, building a fortress, assigning his men to shifts and using stones from the mosque and the cemetery.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite the delays caused by heat and malaria, it was completed in November 1511, its surviving door now known as "A Famosa" ('the famous').
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] It was possibly then that Afonso had a large stone engraved with the names of the participants in the conquest.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] To quell disagreements over the order of the names, he had it set facing the wall, with the single inscription *Lapidem quem reprobaverunt aedificantes* (Latin for "The stone the builders rejected", from David's prophecy, Psalm 118:22–23) on the front.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He settled the Portuguese administration, reappointing Rui de Araújo as factor, a post assigned before his 1509 arrest, and appointing rich merchant Nina Chatu to replace the previous Bendahara.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Besides assisting in the governance of the city and the first Portuguese coinage, he provided the junks for several diplomatic missions.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Meanwhile, Afonso arrested and had executed the powerful Javanese merchant Utimuti Raja who, after being appointed to a position in the Portuguese administration as representative of the Javanese population, had maintained contacts with the exiled royal family.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 20 November 1511 Afonso sailed from Malacca to the coast of Malabar on the old *Flor de la Mar* carrack that had served to support the conquest of Malacca.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite its unsound condition, he used it to transport the treasure amassed in the conquest, given its large capacity.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He wanted to give the court of King Manuel a show of Malaccan treasures.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] There were also offerings from the Ayutthaya Kingdom (Thailand) to the king of Portugal, and all his own fortune.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On the voyage, the *Flor de la Mar* was wrecked in a storm, and Afonso barely escaped drowning.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Most Muslim and Gujarati merchants having fled the city, Afonso invested in diplomatic efforts demonstrating generosity to Southeast Asian merchants, like the Chinese, to encourage good relations with the Portuguese.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Knowing of Siamese ambitions over Malacca, Afonso sent Duarte Fernandes in a diplomatic mission to the Ayutthaya Kingdom (Thailand), returning in a Chinese junk.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was one of the Portuguese who had been arrested in Malacca, having gathered knowledge about the culture of the region.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] There he was the first European to arrive, establishing amicable relations between the kingdom of Portugal and the court of the king of Siam Ramathibodi II, returning with a Siamese envoy bearing gifts and letters to Afonso and the king of Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In November, after having secured Malacca and learning the location of the then secret "spice islands", Afonso sent three ships to find them, led by trusted António de Abreu with deputy commander Francisco Serrão.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Malay sailors were recruited to guide them through Java, the Lesser Sunda Islands and the Ambon Island to Banda Islands, where they arrived in early 1512.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] There they remained for a month, buying and filling their ships with nutmeg and cloves.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] António de Abreu then sailed to Amboina whilst Serrão sailed towards the Moluccas, but he was shipwrecked near Seram.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Sultan Abu Lais of Ternate heard of their stranding, and, seeing a chance to ally himself with a powerful foreign nation, brought them to Ternate in 1512 where they were permitted to build a fort on the island, the *Forte de São João Baptista de Ternate*, built in 1522.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso returned from Malacca to Cochin, but could not sail to Goa as it faced a serious revolt headed by the forces of Ismael Adil Shah, the Sultan of Bijapur, commanded by Rasul Khan and his countrymen.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] During Afonso's absence from Malacca, the Portuguese who opposed the taking of Goa had waived its possession, even writing to the king that it would be best to let it go.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Held up by the monsoon and with few forces available, Afonso had to wait for the arrival of reinforcement fleets headed by his nephew D.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Garcia de Noronha, and Jorge de Mello Pereira.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] While at Cochin, Albuquerque started a school.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In a private letter to King Manuel I, he stated that he had found a chest full of books with which to teach the children of married Portuguese settlers (*casados*) and Christian converts, of which there were about a hundred, to read and write.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 10 September 1512, Afonso sailed from Cochin to Goa with fourteen ships carrying 1,700 soldiers.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Determined to recapture the fortress, he ordered trenches dug and a wall breached.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] But on the day of the planned final assault, Rasul Khan surrendered.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso demanded the fort be handed over with its artillery, ammunition and horses, and the deserters to be given up.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Some had joined Rasul Khan when the Portuguese were forced to flee Goa in May 1510, others during the recent siege.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Rasul Khan consented, on condition that their lives be spared.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He did spare the lives of the deserters, but had them horribly mutilated.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] One such renegade was Fernão Lopes, bound for Portugal in custody, who escaped at the island of Saint Helena and led a 'Robinson Crusoe' life for many years.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After such measures the town became the most prosperous Portuguese settlement in India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In December 1512 an envoy from Ethiopia arrived at Goa.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Mateus was sent by the regent queen Eleni, following the arrival of the Portuguese from Socotra in 1507, as an ambassador for the king of Portugal in search of a coalition to help face growing Muslim influence.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was received in Goa with great honour by Afonso, as a long-sought "Prester John" envoy.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] His arrival was announced by King Manuel to Pope Leo X in 1513.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Although Mateus faced the distrust of Afonso's rivals, who tried to prove he was some impostor or Muslim spy, Afonso sent him to Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The king is described as having wept with joy at their report.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In February 1513, while Mateus was in Portugal, Afonso sailed to the Red Sea with a force of about 1000 Portuguese and 400 Malabaris.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was under orders to secure that channel for Portugal.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Socotra had proved ineffective to control the Red Sea entrance and was abandoned, and Afonso's hint that Massawa could be a good Portuguese base might have been influenced by Mateus' reports.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Knowing that the Mamluks were preparing a second fleet at Suez, he wanted to advance before reinforcements arrived in Aden, and accordingly laid siege to the city.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Aden was a fortified city, but although he had scaling ladders they broke during the chaotic attack.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After half a day of fierce battle, Afonso was forced to retreat.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab, with the first European fleet to have sailed this route.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He attempted to reach Jeddah, but the winds were unfavourable and so he sheltered at Kamaran island in May, until sickness among the men and lack of fresh water forced him to retreat.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In August 1513, after a second attempt to reach Aden, he returned to India with no substantial results.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In order to destroy the power of Egypt, he wrote to King Manuel of the idea of diverting the course of the Nile river to render the whole country barren.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He also intended to steal the body of the Islamic prophet, Muhammad, and hold it for ransom until all Muslims had left the Holy Land.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Although Albuquerque's expedition failed to reach Suez, such an incursion into the Red Sea by a Christian fleet for the first time in history stunned the Muslim world, and panic spread in Cairo.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque achieved during his term a favourable end to hostilities between the Portuguese and the Zamorin of Calicut, which had lasted since the massacre of the Portuguese in Calicut in 1502.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] As naval trade faltered and vassals defected, with no foreseeable solutions to the conflict with the Portuguese, the court of the Zamorin fell to in-fighting.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The ruling Zamorin was assassinated and replaced by a rival, under the instigation of Albuquerque, permitting peace talks to commence.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The Portuguese were allowed to build a fortress in Calicut itself, and acquired rights to obtain as much pepper and ginger as they wished, at stipulated prices, and half the customs duties of Calicut as yearly tribute.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Construction of the fortress began immediately, under the supervision of chief architect Tomás Fernandes.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] With peace concluded, in 1514 Afonso devoted himself to governing Goa and receiving embassies from Indian governors, strengthening the city and encouraging marriages of Portuguese men and local women.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] At that time, Portuguese women were barred from traveling overseas in order to maintain discipline among the men on board the ships.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1511 under a policy which Afonso promulgated, the Portuguese government encouraged their explorers to marry local women.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] To promote settlement, the King of Portugal granted freeman status and exemption from Crown taxes to Portuguese men (known as *casados*, or "married men") who ventured overseas and married local women.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] With Afonso's encouragement, mixed marriages flourished, giving birth to Portuguese-Indians or *mestiços*.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He appointed local people for positions in the Portuguese administration and did not interfere with local traditions (except "sati", the practice of immolating widows, which he banned).
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In March 1514 King Manuel sent to Pope Leo X a huge and exotic embassy led by Tristão da Cunha, who toured the streets of Rome in an extravagant procession of animals from the colonies and wealth from the Indies.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] His reputation reached its peak, laying foundations of the Portuguese Empire in the East.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In early 1514, Afonso sent ambassadors to Gujarat's Sultan Muzaffar Shah II, ruler of Cambay, to seek permission to build a fort on Diu, India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The mission returned without an agreement, but diplomatic gifts were exchanged, including an Indian rhinoceros.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso sent the rhino to King Manuel, making it the first living example of a rhinoceros seen in Europe since the Roman Empire.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] King Manuel named the rhino Genda after the Gujarat word for ball, and later gifted it to Pope Leo X, but before completing its journey to Italy the boat carrying the rhino sank and the animal drowned.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1515, German artist Albrecht Dürer created his famous woodcut known as Dürer's Rhinoceros, based on a description from a letter and a brief sketch made by an unknown artist who had seen the actual animal.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Dürer's interpretation of the rhino cemented the idea of how a rhino should look like in people's mindsets up until the late-eighteenth century.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1513, at Cannanore, Afonso was visited by a Persian ambassador from Shah Ismail I, who had sent ambassadors to Gujarat, Ormuz and Bijapur.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The shah's ambassador to Bijapur invited Afonso to send back an envoy to Persia.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Miguel Ferreira was sent via Ormuz to Tabriz, where he had several interviews with the shah about common goals of defeating the Mamluk sultan.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] At the same time, Albuquerque decided to conclude the effective conquest of Hormuz.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He had learned that after the Portuguese retreat in 1507, a young king was reigning under the influence of a powerful Persian vizier, Reis Hamed, whom the king greatly feared.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] At Ormuz in March 1515, Afonso met the king and asked the vizier to be present.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He then had him immediately stabbed and killed by his entourage, thus "freeing" the terrified king, so the island in the Persian Gulf yielded to him without resistance and remained a vassal state of the Portuguese Empire.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Ormuz itself would not be Persian territory for another century, until an English-Persian alliance finally expelled the Portuguese in 1622.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] At Ormuz, Afonso met with Miguel Ferreira, returning with rich presents and an ambassador, carrying a letter from the Persian potentate Shah Ismael, inviting Afonso to become a leading lord in Persia.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] There he remained, engaging in diplomatic efforts, receiving envoys and overseeing the construction of the new fortress, while becoming increasingly ill.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] His illness was reported as early as September 1515.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In November 1515, he embarked on a journey back to Goa.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] At this time, his political enemies at the Portuguese court were planning his downfall.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] They had lost no opportunity in stirring up the jealousy of King Manuel against him, insinuating that Afonso intended to usurp power in Portuguese India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] While on his return voyage from Ormuz in the Persian Gulf, near the harbor of Chaul, he received news of a Portuguese fleet arriving from Europe, bearing dispatches announcing that he was to be replaced by his personal foe, Lopo Soares de Albergaria.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Feeling himself near death, he donned the surcoat of the Order of Santiago, of which he was a knight, and drew up his will, appointed the captain and senior officials of Ormuz, and organized a final council with his captains to decide the main matters affecting the Portuguese State of India.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He wrote a brief letter to King Manuel, asking him to confer onto his natural son "all of the high honors and rewards" that Afonso had received, and assuring Manuel of his loyalty.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 16 December 1515, Afonso de Albuquerque died within sight of Goa.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] As his death was known, in the city "great wailing arose", and many took to the streets to witness his body carried on a chair by his main captains, in a procession lit by torches amidst the crowd.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso's body was buried in Goa, according to his will, in the Church of Nossa Senhora da Serra (Our Lady of the Hill), which he had been built in 1513 to thank the Madonna for his escape from Kamaran island.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] That night, the population of Goa, both Hindu and Portuguese, gathered to mourn his death.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In Portugal, King Manuel's zigzagging policies continued, still trapped by the constraints of real-time medieval communication between Lisbon and India and unaware that Afonso was dead.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He organized a new Portuguese navy in Asia, with orders that Afonso (if he was still in India), be made commander-in-chief against the Sultan of Cairo's armies.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Manuel would afterwards learn that Afonso had died many months earlier, and that his reversed decision had been delivered many months too late.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] After 51 years, in 1566, his body was moved to Nossa Senhora da Graça church in Lisbon, which was ruined and rebuilt after the 1755 Great Lisbon earthquake.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] King Manuel I of Portugal was belatedly convinced of Afonso's loyalty, and endeavoured to atone for his lack of confidence in Afonso by heaping honours upon his son, Brás de Albuquerque (1500–1580), whom he renamed "Afonso" in memory of the father.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso de Albuquerque was a prolific writer, having sent numerous letters during his governorship, covering topics from minor issues to major strategies.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1557 his son published his biography under the title *Commentarios do Grande Affonso d'Alboquerque*.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1572, Afonso's actions were described in *The Lusiads*, the Portuguese main epic poem by Luís Vaz de Camões (Canto X, strophes 40–49).
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] The poet praises his achievements, but has the muses frown upon the harsh rule of his men, of whom Camões was almost a contemporary fellow.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1934, Afonso was celebrated by Fernando Pessoa in *Mensagem*, a symbolist epic.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] In the first part of this work, called "Brasão" (Coat-of-Arms), he relates Portuguese historical protagonists to each of the fields in the Portuguese coat-of-arms, Afonso being one of the wings of the griffin headed by Henry the Navigator, the other wing being King John II.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] A variety of mango, which was created by Portuguese Jesuits in Goa via grafting techniques, was named in his honour.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Numerous homages have been paid to Afonso.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] He is featured in the Padrão dos Descobrimentos monument.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] There is a square named after him in Lisbon, which also features a bronze statue, as well as a prominent statue of his enrobed figure in a garden square in Bairro Gomes da Costa in Porto.
[src:line-of-battle/afonso-de-albuquerque] Two Portuguese Navy ships have been named in his honour: the sloop NRP *Afonso de Albuquerque* (1884) and the warship NRP *Afonso de Albuquerque* (1934).
[src:line-of-battle/aftercastle] The **aftercastle** (or **sterncastle**, sometimes **aftcastle**) is the stern structure behind the mizzenmast and above the transom on large sailing ships, such as carracks, caravels, galleons and galleasses.
[src:line-of-battle/aftercastle] It usually houses the captain's cabin and perhaps additional cabins and is crowned by the poop deck, which on men-of-war provided a heightened platform from which to fire upon other ships; it was also a place of defence in the event of boarding.
[src:line-of-battle/aftercastle] More common, but much smaller, is the forecastle.
[src:line-of-battle/aftercastle] The corresponding term *forecastle* today is also used to describe the upper deck of a sailing ship forward of the foremast in general.
[src:line-of-battle/aftercastle] As sailing ships evolved, the aftercastle gave way to the quarterdeck, whose span ran all the way to the main mast.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The **line of battle** or the **battle line** is a tactic in naval warfare in which a fleet of ships (known as ships of the line) forms a line end to end.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The first example of its use as a tactic is disputed—it has been variously claimed for dates ranging from 1502 to 1652.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Line-of-battle tactics were in widespread use by 1675.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Compared with prior naval tactics, in which two opposing ships closed on one another for individual combat, the line of battle has the advantage that each ship in the line can fire its broadside without fear of hitting a friendly ship.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] This means that in a given period, the fleet can fire more shots.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Another advantage is that a relative movement of the line in relation to some part of the enemy fleet allows for a systematic concentration of fire on that part.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The other fleet can avoid this by manoeuvring in a line itself, with a result typical for sea battles since 1675: two fleets sail alongside one another (or on the opposite tack).
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The first recorded mention of the use of a line of battle tactic is to be found in the *Instructions*, provided in 1500 by Manuel I, king of Portugal, to the commander of a fleet dispatched to the Indian Ocean.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The precision in the *Instructions* suggests that the tactic was in place before this date.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Portuguese fleets overseas deployed in line ahead, firing one broadside and then putting about in order to return and discharge the other, resolving battles by gunnery alone.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] In a treatise of 1555, *The Art of War at Sea*, Portuguese theorist on naval warfare and shipbuilding, Fernão de Oliveira, recognized that at sea, the Portuguese "fight at a distance, as if from walls and fortresses...".
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] He recommended the single line ahead as the ideal combat formation.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Line-of-battle tactics had been used by the Fourth Portuguese India Armada at the Battle of Calicut (1503), under Vasco da Gama, near Malabar against a Muslim fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] One of the earliest recorded deliberate uses is documented in the First Battle of Cannanore between the Third Portuguese India Armada under João da Nova and the naval forces of Calicut, earlier in the same year.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Others place the first line of battle in the Battle of Cochin.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Another early, but different form of this strategy, was used in 1507 by Afonso de Albuquerque at the entrance to the Persian Gulf, in the first conquest of Ormuz.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Albuquerque commanded a fleet of six carracks manned by 460 men, and entered Ormuz Bay, being surrounded by 250 warships and a 20,000 men army on land.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Albuquerque made his small fleet (but powerful in its artillery) circle like a carrousel, but in a line end-to-end, and destroyed most of the ships that surrounded his squadron.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] From the mid-16th century, the cannon gradually became the most important weapon in naval warfare, replacing boarding actions as the decisive factor in combat.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] At the same time, the natural tendency in the design of galleons was for longer ships with lower forecastles and aftercastles, which meant faster, more stable vessels.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] These newer warships could mount more cannons along the sides of their decks, concentrating their firepower along their broadside, while presenting a lower target to their enemy.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Until the mid-17th century, the tactics of a fleet were often to "charge" the enemy, firing bow chaser cannon, which did not deploy the broadside to its best effect.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] These new vessels required new tactics, and "since ... almost all the artillery is found upon the sides of a ship of war, hence it is the beam that must necessarily and always be turned toward the enemy.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] On the other hand, it is necessary that the sight of the latter must never be interrupted by a friendly ship.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Only one formation allows the ships of the same fleet to satisfy fully these conditions.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] That formation is the line ahead [column].
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] This line, therefore, is imposed as the only order of battle, and consequently as the basis of all fleet tactics." The Dutch admiral Maarten Tromp first used the line of battle tactic in the Fight in the Channel, although some have disputed this.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Captains on both sides of the First Anglo-Dutch War appear to have experimented with the technique in 1652, possibly including Robert Blake at the Battle of Dover (19 May 1652).
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Tromp faced Blake as he approached from Rye with 12 ships.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] After Tromp refused to strike sail in salute, a battle took place, but the Dutch, despite their superior numbers, failed to capture any English ships.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The engagement was, according to the historian Ben Wilson, "a good old-fashioned melee lacking any sophisticated tactics".
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The Battle of the Kentish Knock (28 September 1652) revealed the weakness of the Dutch fleet, largely consisting of smaller ships, against the English.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The Dutch consequently began a large shipbuilding programme.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The Battle of Dungeness (30 November 1652) was a victory for the Dutch, and led to the revitalisation of the Commonwealth Navy.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] After 1652, battles would be determined by the ability of a line of battle to not be broken down.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The line was difficult to maintain when ships performed differently from each other and were affected by the sea conditions and the "chaos of conflict".
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] At the Battle of Portland (18–20 February 1653), the English were scattered at the start of the battle, and so were unable to attack the Dutch fleet effectively.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] It was at Portland that Monck saw how little control admirals had in controlling a fleet and passing commands to his ships.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] One of the first precise written instructions adopting the line of battle tactic were contained in the English Navy's Fighting Instructions, written by Blake and his colleagues, and published in 1653.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] *Instructions for the better ordering of the Fleet in Fighting*, issued on 29 March 1653, was the first clear evidence of the line of battle becoming official policy.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] During the Battle of the Gabbard (2/3 June 1653), both fleets began parallel to each other, arranged in three squadrons nose to tail.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The English ships were able to fire continuous broadsides, resulting in terrible loss of life and damage to the Dutch fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The Dutch were unable to approach the enemy at close quarters, their preferred tactic.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] This usually prevailed if they could isolate and attack individual ships.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The tactic revealed by the Battle of the Gabbard was not new to naval warfare, but was a consequence of the reforms imposed on the English navy.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The New Fighting Instructions meant that senior officers could more easily control their ship captains, who could no longer easily evade fighting, or race heroically ahead of the rest of the fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The line-of-battle tactic favoured very large ships that could sail steadily and maintain their place in the line in the face of heavy fire.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The change toward the line of battle also depended on an increased disciplining of society and the demands of powerful centralized government to keep permanent fleets led by a corps of professional officers.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] These officers were better able to manage and communicate between the ships they commanded than the merchant crews that often comprised large parts of a navy's force.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The new type of warfare that developed during the early modern period was marked by a successively stricter organization.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Battle formations became standardized, based on calculated ideal models.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The increased power of states at the expense of individual landowners led to increasingly larger armies and navies.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] A ship that was powerful enough to stand in the line of battle came to be called a *ship of the line of battle*, or *line of battle ship*.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] In time this became shortened to *battleship*.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The main problem with the line of battle was that when the fleets were of similar size, naval actions using it were generally indecisive.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The French in particular were adept at gunnery and would generally take the leeward position to enable their fleet to retire downwind while continuing to fire chain-shot at long range to bring down masts.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Eventually so many vessels in a line would be damaged that they would be forced to retire for repairs while the French took few casualties and very little damage.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Fleet commanders sometimes met with greater success by altering or abandoning the line of battle outright by breaking the enemy line and moving through it, as occurred during the Four Days Battle, Battle of Schooneveld, and the Battle of Trafalgar.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Another tactic cut off and isolated part of the enemy's line while concentrating a stronger force on it (as happened during the Battle of Texel and the Battle of the Saintes).
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] If the opposing fleets were of similar size, a portion of the line might be overwhelmed by focused gunfire of the entire enemy line by a tactic known as *doubling*.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Ships broke through the enemy line and then, acting simultaneously with other vessels that remained on the original side, would engage the enemy fleet.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] In the years following the defeat of Napoleon at the Battle of Waterloo in 1815, the British Admiralty carried out a radical reform of ship design – between 1810 and 1840, every detail was altered, and more advances occurred during this period than had happened since the 1660s.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] There was, however, no change in the principle of the tactic of a line of battle.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] These alterations were superseded by changes brought about by the advance of steam power and industrially-produced armaments.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Marine steam engines replaced wind power during the 19th century, with HMS *Ajax* converted to steam in 1846, becoming the first steam ship of the line.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The Crimean War showed that sailing ships needed to be converted if they were to be of any military use.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The introduction of the gun turret, which made it impossible to have ships with a full rig, meant that by the 1870s, sail power had been abandoned.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] Battleships of the line were still in use in the early 20th century, using steam-driven propellers and armed with turrets.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] With the introduction of ironclad warships, ramming again became a method of attack, as occurred at the Battle of Lissa (1866), the first ever fleet engagement involving ironclad ships.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] When ramming fell out of fashion, the logic of the line of battle tactic returned.
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] It was used in the Battle of Tsushima (1905), the Battle of Jutland (1916), and – for the last time – in the Battle of Surigao Strait (1944).
[src:line-of-battle/line-of-battle] The development of aircraft carriers as well as a wide variety of anti-ship missiles, particularly those that were cruise guided or had long range, meant that gun engagements were no longer decisive, so that there was no longer any need for a line-of-battle formation.
